# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: americas
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The **ABO blood group system** is used to denote the presence of one, both, or neither of the A and B antigens on erythrocytes (red blood cells).
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] For human blood transfusions, it is the most important of the 48 different blood type (or group) classification systems currently recognized by the International Society of Blood Transfusions (ISBT) as of June 2025.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] A mismatch in this serotype (or in various others) can cause a potentially fatal adverse reaction after a transfusion, or an unwanted immune response to an organ transplant.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Such mismatches are rare in modern medicine.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The associated anti-A and anti-B antibodies are usually IgM antibodies, produced in the first years of life by sensitization to environmental substances such as food, bacteria, and viruses.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The ABO blood types were discovered by Karl Landsteiner in 1901; he received the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1930 for this discovery.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] ABO blood types are also present in other primates such as apes, monkeys and Old World monkeys.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The ABO blood types were first discovered by an Austrian physician, Karl Landsteiner, working at the Pathological-Anatomical Institute of the University of Vienna (now Medical University of Vienna).
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] In 1900, he found that red blood cells would clump together (agglutinate) when mixed in test tubes with sera from different persons, and that some human blood also agglutinated with animal blood.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] This was the first evidence that blood variations exist in humans — it was believed that all humans have similar blood.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The next year, in 1901, he made a definitive observation that blood serum of an individual would agglutinate with only those of certain individuals.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Based on this he classified human blood into three groups, namely group A, group B, and group C.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] He defined that group A blood agglutinates with group B, but never with its own type.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Similarly, group B blood agglutinates with group A.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Group C blood is different in that it agglutinates with both A and B.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] This was the discovery of blood groups for which Landsteiner was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1930.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] In his paper, he referred to the specific blood group interactions as isoagglutination, and also introduced the concept of agglutinins (antibodies), which is the actual basis of antigen-antibody reaction in the ABO system.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Thus, he discovered two antigens (agglutinogens A and B) and two antibodies (agglutinins — anti-A and anti-B).
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] His third group (C) indicated absence of both A and B antigens, but contains anti-A and anti-B.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The following year, his students Adriano Sturli and Alfred von Decastello discovered the fourth type (but not naming it, and simply referred to it as "no particular type").
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] In 1910, Ludwik Hirszfeld and Emil Freiherr von Dungern introduced the term 0 (null) for the group Landsteiner designated as C, and AB for the type discovered by Sturli and von Decastello.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] They were also the first to explain the genetic inheritance of the blood groups.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Czech serologist Jan Janský independently introduced blood type classification in 1907 in a local journal.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] He used the Roman numerical I, II, III, and IV (corresponding to modern O, A, B, and AB).
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Unknown to Janský, an American physician William L.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Moss devised a slightly different classification using the same numerical; his I, II, III, and IV corresponding to modern AB, A, B, and O.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] These two systems created confusion and potential danger in medical practice.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Moss's system was adopted in Britain, France, and US, while Janský's was preferred in most European countries and some parts of US.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] To resolve the chaos, the American Association of Immunologists, the Society of American Bacteriologists, and the Association of Pathologists and Bacteriologists made a joint recommendation in 1921 that the Jansky classification be adopted based on priority.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] But it was not followed particularly where Moss's system had been used.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] In 1927, Landsteiner had moved to the Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research in New York.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] As a member of a committee of the National Research Council concerned with blood grouping, he suggested to substitute Janský's and Moss's systems with the letters O, A, B, and AB.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The new system was gradually accepted and by the early 1950s, it was universally followed.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The first practical use of blood typing in transfusion was by an American physician Reuben Ottenberg in 1907.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Large-scale application began during the First World War (1914–1915) when citric acid began to be used for blood clot prevention.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Felix Bernstein demonstrated the correct blood group inheritance pattern of multiple alleles at one locus in 1924.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Watkins and Morgan, in England, discovered that the ABO epitopes were conferred by sugars, to be specific, *N*-acetylgalactosamine for the A-type and galactose for the B-type.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] After much published literature claiming that the ABH substances were all attached to glycosphingolipids, Finne *et al*.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] (1978) found that the human erythrocyte glycoproteins contain polylactosamine chains that contains ABH substances attached and represent the majority of the antigens.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The main glycoproteins carrying the ABH antigens were identified to be the Band 3 and Band 4.5 proteins and glycophorin.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Later, Yamamoto's group showed the precise glycosyl transferase set that confers the A, B and O epitopes.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Blood groups are inherited from both parents.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The ABO blood type is controlled by a single gene (the ABO gene) with three types of alleles inferred from classical genetics: *i*, *IA*, and *IB*.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The *I* designation stands for **isoagglutinogen**, another term for antigen.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The gene encodes a glycosyltransferase—that is, an enzyme that modifies the carbohydrate content of the red blood cell antigens.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The gene is located on the long arm of the ninth chromosome (9q34).
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The *IA* allele gives type A, *IB* gives type B, and *i* gives type O.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] As both *IA* and *IB* are dominant over *i*, only *ii* people have type O blood.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Individuals with *IAIA* or *IAi* have type A blood, and individuals with *IBIB* or *IBi* have type B.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] *IAIB* people have both phenotypes, because A and B express a special dominance relationship: codominance, which means that type A and B parents can have an AB child.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] A couple with type A and type B can also have a type O child if they are both heterozygous (*IBi* and *IAi*).
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The *cis-AB* phenotype has a single enzyme that creates both A and B antigens.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The resulting red blood cells do not usually express A or B antigen at the same level that would be expected on common group A1 or B red blood cells, which can help solve the problem of an apparently genetically impossible blood group.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Individuals with the rare Bombay phenotype (hh) produce antibodies against the A, B, and O groups and can only receive transfusions from other hh individuals.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The table above summarizes the various blood groups that children may inherit from their parents.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Genotypes are shown in the second column and in small print for the offspring: AO and AA both test as type A; BO and BB test as type B.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The four possibilities represent the combinations obtained when one allele is taken from each parent; each has a 25% chance, but some occur more than once.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The text above them summarizes the outcomes.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Historically, ABO blood tests were used in paternity testing, but in 1957 only 50% of American men falsely accused were able to use them as evidence against paternity.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Occasionally, the blood types of children are not consistent with expectations—for example, a type O child can be born to an AB parent—due to rare situations, such as Bombay phenotype and cis AB.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The A blood type contains about 20 subgroups, of which A1 and A2 are the most common (over 99%).
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] A1 makes up about 80% of all A-type blood, with A2 making up almost all of the rest.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] These two subgroups are not always interchangeable as far as transfusion is concerned, as some A2 individuals produce antibodies against the A1 antigen.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Complications can sometimes arise in rare cases when typing the blood.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] With the development of DNA sequencing, it has been possible to identify a much larger number of alleles at the ABO locus, each of which can be categorized as A, B, or O in terms of the reaction to transfusion, but which can be distinguished by variations in the DNA sequence.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The same study also identified 18 rare alleles, which generally have a weaker glycosylation activity.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] People with weak alleles of A can sometimes express anti-A antibodies, though these are usually not clinically significant as they do not stably interact with the antigen at body temperature.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Cis AB is another rare variant, in which A and B antigens are transmitted together from a single parent.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The distribution of the blood groups A, B, O and AB varies across the world according to the population.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] There are also variations in blood type distribution within human subpopulations.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The native Celts tended to have more type O blood, while the other populations tended to have more type A.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The two common O alleles, O01 and O02, share their first 261 nucleotides with the group A allele A01.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] However, unlike the group A allele, a guanosine base is subsequently deleted.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] A premature stop codon results from this frame-shift mutation.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] This variant is found worldwide, and likely predates human migration from Africa.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The O01 allele is considered to predate the O02 allele.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Some evolutionary biologists theorize that there are four main lineages of the ABO gene and that mutations creating type O have occurred at least three times in humans.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] From oldest to youngest, these lineages comprise the following alleles: *A101/A201/O09*, *B101*, *O02* and *O01*.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The continued presence of the O alleles is hypothesized to be the result of balancing selection.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Both theories contradict the previously held theory that type O blood evolved first.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] It is possible that food and environmental antigens (bacterial, viral, or plant antigens) have epitopes similar enough to A and B glycoprotein antigens.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The antibodies created against these environmental antigens in the first years of life can cross-react with ABO-incompatible red blood cells that it comes in contact with during blood transfusion later in life.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Anti-A antibodies are hypothesized to originate from immune response towards influenza virus, whose epitopes are similar enough to the α-D-N-galactosamine on the A glycoprotein to be able to elicit a cross-reaction.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Anti-B antibodies are hypothesized to originate from antibodies produced against Gram-negative bacteria, such as *E. coli*, cross-reacting with the α-D-galactose on the B glycoprotein.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] However, it is more likely that the force driving evolution of allele diversity is simply negative frequency-dependent selection; cells with rare variants of membrane antigens are more easily distinguished by the immune system from pathogens carrying antigens from other hosts.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Thus, individuals possessing rare types are better equipped to detect pathogens.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The high within-population diversity observed in human populations would, then, be a consequence of natural selection on individuals.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The carbohydrate molecules on the surfaces of red blood cells have roles in cell membrane integrity, cell adhesion, membrane transportation of molecules, and acting as receptors for extracellular ligands, and enzymes.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] ABO antigens are found having similar roles on epithelial cells as well as red blood cells.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The ABO antigen is also expressed on the von Willebrand factor (vWF) glycoprotein, which participates in hemostasis (control of bleeding).
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] In fact, having type O blood predisposes to bleeding, as 30% of the total genetic variation observed in plasma vWF is explained by the effect of the ABO blood group, and individuals with group O blood normally have significantly lower plasma levels of vWF (and Factor VIII) than do non-O individuals.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] In addition, vWF is degraded more rapidly due to the higher prevalence of blood group O with the Cys1584 variant of vWF (an amino acid polymorphism in VWF): the gene for ADAMTS13 (vWF-cleaving protease) maps to human chromosome 9 band q34.2, the same locus as ABO blood type.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Higher levels of vWF are more common amongst people who have had ischemic stroke (from blood clotting) for the first time.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The results of this study found that the occurrence was not affected by ADAMTS13 polymorphism, and the only significant genetic factor was the person's blood group.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] ABO(H) blood group antigens are also carried by other hemostatically relevant glycoproteins, such as platelet glycoprotein Ibα, which is a ligand for vWF on platelets.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The significance of ABO(H) antigen expression on these other hemostatic glycoproteins is not fully defined, but may also be relevant for bleeding and thrombosis.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] ABO blood group incompatibilities between the mother and child do not usually cause hemolytic disease of the newborn (HDN) because antibodies to the ABO blood groups are usually of the IgM type, which do not cross the placenta.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] However, in an O-type mother, **IgG** ABO antibodies are produced and the baby can potentially develop ABO hemolytic disease of the newborn.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] In human cells, the ABO alleles and their encoded glycosyltransferases have been described in several oncologic conditions.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Using anti-GTA/GTB monoclonal antibodies, it was demonstrated that a loss of these enzymes was correlated to malignant bladder and oral epithelia.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Furthermore, the expression of ABO blood group antigens in normal human tissues is dependent the type of differentiation of the epithelium.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] In most human carcinomas, including oral carcinoma, a significant event as part of the underlying mechanism is decreased expression of the A and B antigens.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Several studies have observed that a relative down-regulation of GTA and GTB occurs in oral carcinomas in association with tumor development.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] More recently, a genome wide association study (GWAS) has identified variants in the ABO locus associated with susceptibility to pancreatic cancer.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] In addition, another large GWAS study has associated ABO-histo blood groups as well as FUT2 secretor status with the presence in the intestinal microbiome of specific bacterial species.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] In this case the association was with *Bacteroides* and *Faecalibacterium spp*.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] *Bacteroides* of the same OTU (operational taxonomic unit) have been shown to be associated with inflammatory bowel disease, thus the study suggests an important role for the ABO histo-blood group antigens as candidates for direct modulation of the human microbiome in health and disease.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] A multi-locus genetic risk score study based on a combination of 27 loci, including the ABO gene, identified individuals at increased risk for both incident and recurrent coronary artery disease events, as well as an enhanced clinical benefit from statin therapy.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The study was based on a community cohort study (the Malmo Diet and Cancer study) and four additional randomized controlled trials of primary prevention cohorts (JUPITER and ASCOT) and secondary prevention cohorts (CARE and PROVE IT-TIMI 22).
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] In April 2007, an international team of researchers announced in the journal *Nature Biotechnology* an inexpensive and efficient way to convert types A, B, and AB blood into type O.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] This is done by using glycosidase enzymes from specific bacteria to strip the blood group antigens from red blood cells.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The removal of A and B antigens still does not address the problem of the Rh blood group antigen on the blood cells of Rh positive individuals, and so blood from Rh negative donors must be used.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The modified blood is named "enzyme converted to O" (ECO blood) but despite the early success of converting B- to O-type RBCs and clinical trials without adverse effects transfusing into A- and O-type patients, the technology has not yet become clinical practice.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Another approach to the blood antigen problem is the manufacture of artificial blood, which could act as a substitute in emergencies.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] In Japan and other parts of East Asia, there is a popular belief in blood type personality theory, which claims that blood types predict or influence personality.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] This claim is not scientifically based, and there is scientific consensus that no such link exists; the scientific community considers it a pseudoscience and a superstition.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] The belief originated in the 1930s, when it was introduced as part of Japan's eugenics program.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Its popularity faded following Japan's defeat in World War 2 and Japanese support for eugenics faltered, but it resurfaced in the 1970s by a journalist named Masahiko Nomi.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Despite its status as a pseudoscience, it remains widely popular throughout East Asia.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] Other popular ideas are blood type-specific dietary needs, that group A causes severe hangovers, that group O is associated with better teeth, and that those with group A2 have the highest IQ scores.
[src:americas/abo-blood-group-system] As with blood type personality theory, these and other popular ideas lack scientific evidence, and many are discredited or pseudoscientific.
[src:americas/abya-yala] The first explicit usage of the expression in its political sense was at the 2nd Continental Summit of Indigenous Peoples and Nationalities of Abya Yala, held in Quito in 2004.
[src:americas/abya-yala] The symbolic and ideological significance of this summit is reflected in its rejection of neoliberal globalization, its reaffirmation of Indigenous peoples' rights to territorial autonomy, and its continuity with the earlier declarations made at the 2000 Teotihuacan Summit.
[src:americas/abya-yala] Many Indigenous movements have adopted this designation to replace colonial names such as ‘Latin America’ to express a connection to the land, community and ancestral memory.
[src:americas/acadia] The first capital of Acadia was established in 1605 as Port-Royal.
[src:americas/acadia] Soon after, English forces of Captain Argall, an English ship's captain employed by the Virginia Company of London attacked and burned down the fortified habitation in 1613.
[src:americas/acadia] A new centre for Port-Royal was established nearby, and it remained the longest-serving capital of French Acadia until the British siege of Port Royal in 1710.
[src:americas/acadia] There were six colonial wars in a 74-year period in which British interests tried to capture Acadia, starting with King William's War in 1689.
[src:americas/acadia] French troops from Quebec, Acadians, the Wabanaki Confederacy, and French priests continually raided New England settlements along the border in Maine during these wars.
[src:americas/acadia] Acadia was conquered in 1710 during Queen Anne's War, while New Brunswick and much of Maine remained contested territory.
[src:americas/acadia] Prince Edward Island (Île Saint-Jean) and Cape Breton (Île Royale) remained under French control, as agreed under Article XIII of the Treaty of Utrecht.
[src:americas/acadia] The English took control of Maine by defeating the Wabanaki Confederacy and the French priests during Father Rale's War.
[src:americas/acadia] During King George's War, France and New France made significant attempts to regain mainland Nova Scotia.
[src:americas/acadia] The British took New Brunswick in Father Le Loutre's War, and they took Île Royale and Île Saint-Jean in 1758 following the French and Indian War.
[src:americas/acadia] The territory was eventually divided into British colonies.
[src:americas/acadia] The term Acadia today refers to regions of North America that are historically associated with the lands, descendants, or culture of the former region.
[src:americas/acadia] It particularly refers to regions of the Maritimes with Acadian roots, language, and culture, primarily in New Brunswick, Nova Scotia, the Magdalen Islands and Prince Edward Island, as well as in Maine.
[src:americas/acadia] "Acadia" can also refer to the Acadian diaspora in southern Louisiana, a region also referred to as Acadiana since the early 1960s.
[src:americas/acadia] In the abstract, Acadia refers to the existence of an Acadian culture in any of these regions.
[src:americas/acadia] People living in Acadia are called Acadians, which in Louisiana changed to Cajuns, the more common, rural American, name of Acadians.
[src:americas/acadia] Explorer Giovanni da Verrazzano is credited for originating the designation Acadia on his 16th-century map, where he applied the ancient Greek name "Arcadia" to the entire Atlantic coast north of Virginia.
[src:americas/acadia] "Arcadia" is derived from the Arcadia region in Greece, which had the extended meanings of "refuge" or "idyllic place".
[src:americas/acadia] Henry IV of France chartered a colony south of the St.
[src:americas/acadia] Lawrence River between the 40th and 46th parallels in 1603, and he recognized it as *La Cadie*.
[src:americas/acadia] Samuel de Champlain fixed its present orthography with the *r* omitted, and cartographer William Francis Ganong has shown its gradual progress northeastwards to its resting place in the Atlantic provinces of Canada.
[src:americas/acadia] As an alternative theory, some historians suggest that the name is derived from the indigenous Canadian Mi'kmaw language, in which Cadie means "fertile land".
[src:americas/acadia] The history of Acadia was significantly influenced by the great power conflict between France and England, later Great Britain, that occurred in the 17th and 18th centuries.
[src:americas/acadia] Prior to the arrival of Europeans, the Mi'kmaq had been living in Acadia for at least two to three thousand years.
[src:americas/acadia] Early European settlers were French subjects primarily from the Poitou-Charentes and Aquitaine regions of southwestern France, now known as Nouvelle-Aquitaine.
[src:americas/acadia] The first French settlement was established by Pierre Dugua de Mons, Governor of Acadia, under the authority of the French King, Henri IV, on Saint Croix Island in 1604.
[src:americas/acadia] The following year, the settlement was moved across the Bay of Fundy to Port Royal after a difficult winter on the island and deaths from scurvy.
[src:americas/acadia] There, they constructed a new habitation.
[src:americas/acadia] In 1607, the colony received bad news as Henri IV revoked Sieur de Mons' royal fur monopoly, citing that the income was insufficient to justify supplying the colony further.
[src:americas/acadia] Thus recalled, the last of the French left Port Royal in August 1607.
[src:americas/acadia] Their allies, the Mi'kmaq, agreed to act as custodians of the settlement.
[src:americas/acadia] When the former lieutenant governor, Jean de Biencourt de Poutrincourt et de Saint-Just, returned in 1610, he found the Port Royal habitation just as it was left.
[src:americas/acadia] During the first 80 years of the French presence in Acadia, there were numerous significant battles as the English, Scottish, and Dutch contested the French for possession of the colony.
[src:americas/acadia] These battles happened at Port Royal, Saint John, Cap de Sable (present-day Port La Tour, Nova Scotia), Jemseg, Castine, and Baleine.
[src:americas/acadia] From the 1680s onward, there were six colonial wars that took place in the region (see the French and Indian Wars as well as Father Rale's War and Father Le Loutre's War).
[src:americas/acadia] These wars were fought between New England and New France, and their respective native allies.
[src:americas/acadia] The wars were fought on two fronts: the southern border of Acadia, which New France defined as the Kennebec River in southern Maine and in present-day peninsular Nova Scotia.
[src:americas/acadia] The latter involved preventing the British from taking the capital of Acadia, Port Royal (See Queen Anne's War), establishing themselves at Canso (See Father Rale's War) and founding Halifax (see Father Le Loutre's War).
[src:americas/acadia] From 1640 to 1645, Acadia was plunged into what some historians have described as a civil war.
[src:americas/acadia] The war was between Port Royal, where the Governor of Acadia Charles de Menou d'Aulnay de Charnisay was stationed, and present-day Saint John, New Brunswick, where Governor of Acadia Charles de Saint-Étienne de la Tour was stationed.
[src:americas/acadia] There were four major battles in the war, and d'Aulnay ultimately prevailed over La Tour.
[src:americas/acadia] During King Philip's War (1675–78), the governor was absent from Acadia (having first been imprisoned in Boston during the Dutch occupation of Acadia) and Jean-Vincent d'Abbadie de Saint-Castin was established at the capital of Acadia, Pentagouêt.
[src:americas/acadia] From there he worked with the Abenaki of Acadia to raid British settlements migrating over the border of Acadia.
[src:americas/acadia] British retaliation included attacking deep into Acadia in the Battle of Port La Tour (1677).
[src:americas/acadia] In response to King Philip's War in New England, the native peoples in Acadia joined the Wabanaki Confederacy to form a political and military alliance with New France.
[src:americas/acadia] The Confederacy remained significant military allies to New France through six wars.
[src:americas/acadia] Until the French and Indian War the Wabanaki Confederacy remained the dominant military force in the region.
[src:americas/acadia] There were tensions on the border between New England and Acadia, which New France defined as the Kennebec River in southern Maine.
[src:americas/acadia] English settlers from Massachusetts (whose charter included the Maine area) had expanded their settlements into Acadia.
[src:americas/acadia] During King William's War (1688–97), some Acadians, the Wabanaki Confederacy and the French Priests participated in defending Acadia at its border with New England, which New France defined as the Kennebec River in southern Maine.
[src:americas/acadia] Toward this end, the members of the Wabanaki Confederacy, on the Saint John River and in other places, joined the New France expedition against present-day Bristol, Maine (the siege of Pemaquid (1689)), Salmon Falls and present-day Portland, Maine.
[src:americas/acadia] In response, the New Englanders retaliated by attacking Port Royal and present-day Guysborough.
[src:americas/acadia] In 1694, the Wabanaki Confederacy participated in the Raid on Oyster River at present-day Durham, New Hampshire.
[src:americas/acadia] Two years later, New France, led by Pierre Le Moyne d'Iberville, returned and fought a naval battle in the Bay of Fundy before moving on to raid Bristol, Maine, again.
[src:americas/acadia] In retaliation, the New Englanders, led by Benjamin Church, engaged in a Raid on Chignecto (1696) and the siege of the Capital of Acadia at Fort Nashwaak.
[src:americas/acadia] At the end of the war England returned the territory to France in the Treaty of Ryswick and the borders of Acadia remained the same.
[src:americas/acadia] During Queen Anne's War, some Acadians, the Wabanaki Confederacy and the French priests participated again in defending Acadia at its border with New England.
[src:americas/acadia] They made numerous raids on New England settlements along the border in the Northeast Coast Campaign and the famous Raid on Deerfield.
[src:americas/acadia] In retaliation, Major Benjamin Church went on his fifth and final expedition to Acadia.
[src:americas/acadia] He raided present-day Castine, Maine and continued with raids against Grand Pre, Pisiquid, and Chignecto.
[src:americas/acadia] A few years later, defeated in the siege of Pemaquid (1696), Captain March made an unsuccessful siege on the Capital of Acadia, Port Royal (1707).
[src:americas/acadia] British forces were successful with the siege of Port Royal (1710), while the Wabanaki Confederacy were successful in the nearby Battle of Bloody Creek (1711) and continued raids along the Maine frontier.
[src:americas/acadia] The 1710 conquest of the Acadian capital of Port Royal during the war was confirmed by the Treaty of Utrecht of 1713.
[src:americas/acadia] The British conceded to the French "the island called Cape Breton, as also all others, both in the mouth of the river of St.
[src:americas/acadia] Lawrence, and in the gulph of the same name", and "all manner of liberty to fortify any place or places there." The French established a fortress at Louisbourg, Cape Breton, to guard the sea approaches to Quebec.
[src:americas/acadia] On 23 June 1713, the French residents of Nova Scotia were given one year to declare allegiance to Britain or leave the region.
[src:americas/acadia] In the meantime, the French signalled their preparedness for future hostilities by beginning the construction of Fortress Louisbourg on Île Royale, now Cape Breton Island.
[src:americas/acadia] The British grew increasingly alarmed by the prospect of disloyalty in wartime of the Acadians now under their rule.
[src:americas/acadia] French missionaries worked to maintain the loyalty of Acadians, and to maintain a hold on the mainland part of Acadia.
[src:americas/acadia] During the escalation that preceded Dummer's War (1722–1725), some Acadians, the Wabanaki Confederacy and the French priests persisted in defending Acadia, which had been conceded to the British in the Treaty of Utrecht, at its border against New England.
[src:americas/acadia] The Miꞌkmaq refused to recognize the treaty handing over their land to the English and hostilities resumed.
[src:americas/acadia] The Miꞌkmaq raided the new fort at Canso, Nova Scotia in 1720.
[src:americas/acadia] The Confederacy made numerous raids on New England settlements along the border into New England.
[src:americas/acadia] Towards the end of January 1722, Governor Samuel Shute chose to launch a punitive expedition against Sébastien Rale, a Jesuit missionary, at Norridgewock.
[src:americas/acadia] This breach of the border of Acadia, which had at any rate been ceded to the British, drew all of the tribes of the Wabanaki Confederacy into the conflict.
[src:americas/acadia] Under potential siege by the Confederacy, in May 1722, Lieutenant Governor John Doucett took 22 Miꞌkmaq hostage at Annapolis Royal to prevent the capital from being attacked.
[src:americas/acadia] In July 1722, the Abenaki and Miꞌkmaq created a blockade of Annapolis Royal, with the intent of starving the capital.
[src:americas/acadia] The natives captured 18 fishing vessels and prisoners from present-day Yarmouth to Canso.
[src:americas/acadia] They also seized prisoners and vessels from the Bay of Fundy.
[src:americas/acadia] As a result of the escalating conflict, Massachusetts Governor Shute officially declared war on 22 July 1722.
[src:americas/acadia] The first battle of Father Rale's War happened in the Nova Scotia theatre.
[src:americas/acadia] In response to the blockade of Annapolis Royal, at the end of July 1722, New England launched a campaign to end the blockade and retrieve over 86 New England prisoners taken by the natives.
[src:americas/acadia] One of these operations resulted in the Battle at Jeddore.
[src:americas/acadia] Then in July 1724 a group of sixty Miꞌkmaq and Wolastoqiyik raided Annapolis Royal.
[src:americas/acadia] As a result of Father Rale's War, present-day central Maine fell again to the British with the defeat of Sébastien Rale at Norridgewock and the subsequent retreat of the native population from the Kennebec and Penobscot rivers.
[src:americas/acadia] King George's War began when the war declarations from Europe reached the French fortress at Louisbourg first, on May 3, 1744, and the forces there wasted little time in beginning hostilities.
[src:americas/acadia] Concerned about their overland supply lines to Quebec, they first raided the British fishing port of Canso on May 23, and then organized an attack on Annapolis Royal, then the capital of Nova Scotia.
[src:americas/acadia] However, French forces were delayed in departing Louisbourg, and their Miꞌkmaq and Wolastoqey allies decided to attack on their own in early July.
[src:americas/acadia] Annapolis had received news of the war declaration, and was somewhat prepared when the Indians began besieging Fort Anne.
[src:americas/acadia] Lacking heavy weapons, the Indians withdrew after a few days.
[src:americas/acadia] Then, in mid-August, a larger French force arrived before Fort Anne, but was also unable to mount an effective attack or siege against the garrison, which had received supplies and reinforcements from Massachusetts.
[src:americas/acadia] In 1745, British colonial forces conducted the siege of Port Toulouse (St.
[src:americas/acadia] Peter's) and then captured Fortress Louisbourg after a siege of six weeks.
[src:americas/acadia] France launched a major expedition to recover Acadia in 1746.
[src:americas/acadia] Beset by storms, disease, and finally the death of its commander, the Duc d'Anville, it returned to France in tatters without reaching its objective.
[src:americas/acadia] French officer Jean-Baptiste Nicolas Roch de Ramezay also arrived from Quebec and conducted the Battle at Port-la-Joye on Île Saint-Jean and the Battle of Grand Pré.
[src:americas/acadia] Despite the British capture of the Acadian capital in the siege of Port Royal (1710), Nova Scotia remained primarily occupied by Catholic Acadians and Miꞌkmaq.
[src:americas/acadia] To prevent the establishment of Protestant settlements in the region, Miꞌkmaq raided the early British settlements of present-day Shelburne (1715) and Canso (1720).
[src:americas/acadia] A generation later, Father Le Loutre's War began when Edward Cornwallis arrived to establish Halifax with 13 transports on 21 June 1749.
[src:americas/acadia] The British quickly began to build other settlements.
[src:americas/acadia] To guard against Miꞌkmaq, Acadian and French attacks on the new Protestant settlements, they erected fortifications in Halifax (Citadel Hill) (1749), Dartmouth (1750), Bedford (Fort Sackville) (1751), Lunenburg (1753) and Lawrencetown (1754).
[src:americas/acadia] There were numerous Miꞌkmaq and Acadian raids on these villages such as the Raid on Dartmouth (1751).
[src:americas/acadia] Within 18 months of establishing Halifax, the British also took firm control of peninsular Nova Scotia by building fortifications in all the major Acadian communities: present-day Windsor (Fort Edward, 1750); Grand Pre (Fort Vieux Logis, 1749) and Chignecto (Fort Lawrence, 1750).
[src:americas/acadia] (A British fort already existed at the other major Acadian centre of Annapolis Royal, Nova Scotia.
[src:americas/acadia] Cobequid remained without a fort.) Numerous Miꞌkmaq and Acadian raids took place against these fortifications, such as the siege of Grand Pre (1749).
[src:americas/acadia] In the years after the British conquest, the Acadians refused to swear unconditional oaths of allegiance to the British crown.
[src:americas/acadia] During this time period some Acadians participated in militia operations against the British and maintained vital supply lines to Fortress Louisbourg and Fort Beausejour.
[src:americas/acadia] During the French and Indian War, the British sought to neutralize any military threat Acadians posed and to interrupt the vital supply lines Acadians provided to Louisbourg by deporting them.
[src:americas/acadia] This process began in 1755, after the British captured Fort Beauséjour and began the expulsion of the Acadians with the Bay of Fundy Campaign.
[src:americas/acadia] Between six and seven thousand Acadians were expelled from Nova Scotia to the lower British American colonies.
[src:americas/acadia] Some Acadians eluded capture by fleeing deep into the wilderness or into French-controlled Canada.
[src:americas/acadia] The Quebec town of L'Acadie (now a sector of Saint-Jean-sur-Richelieu) was founded by expelled Acadians.
[src:americas/acadia] After the siege of Louisbourg (1758), a second wave of the expulsion began with the St.
[src:americas/acadia] John River Campaign, Petitcodiac River Campaign, Gulf of St.
[src:americas/acadia] Lawrence Campaign and the Île Saint-Jean Campaign.
[src:americas/acadia] The Acadians and the Wabanaki Confederacy put up a significant resistance to the British throughout the war.
[src:americas/acadia] They repeatedly raided Canso, Lunenburg, Halifax, Chignecto and into New England.
[src:americas/acadia] Any pretense that France might maintain or regain control over the remnants of Acadia came to an end with the fall of Montreal in 1760 and the 1763 Treaty of Paris, which permanently ceded almost all of eastern New France to Britain.
[src:americas/acadia] In 1763, Britain would designate lands west of the Appalachians as the "Indian Reserve", but did not respect Miꞌkmaq title to the Atlantic region, claiming title was obtained from the French.
[src:americas/acadia] The Miꞌkmaq remain in Acadia to this day.
[src:americas/acadia] In Louisiana, the demonym *Acadian* developed into *Cadien*, anglicized as *Cajun,* which was first used as a pejorative term until its later mainstream acceptance.
[src:americas/acadia] Britain eventually moderated its policies and allowed Acadians to return to Nova Scotia.
[src:americas/acadia] However, most of the fertile former Acadian lands were now occupied by British colonists.
[src:americas/acadia] The returning Acadians settled instead in more outlying areas of the original Acadia, such as Cape Breton and the areas which are now New Brunswick and Prince Edward Island.
[src:americas/acadia] Among the Acadian descendants in the Canadian Maritime provinces, there was a revival of cultural awareness which is recognized as an Acadian Renaissance, with a struggle for recognition of Acadians as a distinct group starting in the mid-nineteenth century.
[src:americas/acadia] Some Acadian deputies were elected to legislative assemblies, starting in 1836 with Simon d'Entremont in Nova Scotia.
[src:americas/acadia] Several other provincial and federal members followed in New Brunswick and in Prince Edward Island.
[src:americas/acadia] This period saw the founding of Acadian higher educational institutions: the Saint Thomas Seminary from 1854 to 1862 and then Saint Joseph's College from 1864, both in Memramcook, New Brunswick.
[src:americas/acadia] This was followed by the founding of Acadian newspapers: the weekly *Le Moniteur Acadien* in 1867 and the daily *L'Évangéline* in 1887 (fr), named after the epic poem by Longfellow.
[src:americas/acadia] In New Brunswick the 1870s saw a struggle against the Common Schools Act of 1871, which imposed a non-denominational school system and forbade religious instruction during school hours.
[src:americas/acadia] This led to widespread Acadian protests and school-tax boycotts, culminating in the 1875 riots in the town of Caraquet.
[src:americas/acadia] Finally in 1875 a compromise was reached allowing for some Catholic religious teaching in the schools.
[src:americas/acadia] In the 1880s there began a series of Acadian national conventions.
[src:americas/acadia] The first in 1881 adopted Assumption Day (Aug.15) as the Acadian national holiday.
[src:americas/acadia] The convention favored the argument of the priest Marcel-François Richard (fr) that Acadians are a distinct people which should have a national holiday distinct from that of Quebec (Saint-Jean-Baptiste Day).
[src:americas/acadia] The second convention in 1884 adopted other national symbols including the flag of Acadia designed by Marcel-François Richard, and the anthem Ave maris stella.
[src:americas/acadia] The third convention in 1890 created the Société nationale L'Assomption to promote the interests of the Acadian people in the Maritimes.
[src:americas/acadia] Other Acadian national conventions continued until the fifteenth in 1972.
[src:americas/acadia] In 1885, the author, historian and linguist Pascal Poirier became the first Acadian member of the Senate of Canada.
[src:americas/acadia] By the early twentieth century, some Acadians were chosen for leadership positions in New Brunswick.
[src:americas/acadia] In 1912, Monseigneur Édouard LeBlanc of Nova Scotia was named bishop of Saint John, after a campaign lasting many years to convince the Vatican to appoint an Acadian bishop.
[src:americas/acadia] In 1917, the premier of Prince Edward Island resigned to accept a judicial position, and his Conservative Party chose Aubin-Edmond Arsenault as successor until the next election in 1919.
[src:americas/acadia] Arsenault thus became the first Acadian provincial premier of any province in Canada.
[src:americas/acadia] In 1923, Peter Veniot became the first Acadian premier of New Brunswick when he was chosen by the Liberal Party to complete the term of the retiring premier until 1925.
[src:americas/acadia] The expansion of Acadian influence in the Catholic church continued in 1936 with the creation of the Archdiocese of Moncton whose first archbishop was Louis-Joseph-Arthur Melanson, and whose Cathédrale Notre-Dame de l’Assomption was completed in 1940.
[src:americas/acadia] The new archdiocese was expanded to include new predominantly Acadian dioceses in Bathurst, New Brunswick (1938), in Edmundston (1944) and in Yarmouth, Nova Scotia (1953).
[src:americas/acadia] In 1960, Louis Robichaud became the first Acadian to be elected premier of a Canadian province.
[src:americas/acadia] He was elected premier of New Brunswick in 1960 and served three terms until 1970.
[src:americas/acadia] The Robichaud government created the Université de Moncton in 1963 as a unilingual French-language university, corresponding to the much older unilingual English-language University of New Brunswick.
[src:americas/acadia] In 1964, two different deputy ministers of education were named to direct English-language and French-language school systems respectively.
[src:americas/acadia] In the next few years, the Université de Moncton absorbed the former Saint-Joseph's College, as well as the École Normale (teacher's college) which trained French-speaking teachers for the Acadian schools.
[src:americas/acadia] In 1977, two French-speaking colleges in Northern New Brunswick were transformed into the Edmundston and Shippagan campuses of the Université de Moncton.
[src:americas/acadia] The New Brunswick Equal Opportunity program of 1967 introduced reforms of municipal structures, of health care, of education, and of the administration of justice.
[src:americas/acadia] In general, these changes tended to reduce economic inequality between regions of the province, and therefore tended to favour the disadvantaged Acadian regions.
[src:americas/acadia] The New Brunswick Official Languages Act (1969) declared New Brunswick officially bilingual with English and French having equal status as official languages.
[src:americas/acadia] Residents have the right to receive provincial government services in the official language of their choice.
[src:americas/acadia] The New Brunswick government of Richard Hatfield (1970–87) cooperated with the Government of Canada in including the right to linguistic equality in the province as a part of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms of 1982, so that it cannot be rescinded by any future provincial government.
[src:americas/acadia] Nova Scotia adopted Bill 65 in 1981 to give Acadian schools legal status, and also created a study program including Acadian history and culture.
[src:americas/acadia] The Acadian schools were placed under separate management in 1996.
[src:americas/acadia] Prince Edward Island provided French-language schools in 1980 in areas with a sufficient number of Acadian students, followed by a French-language school commission for the province in 1990.
[src:americas/acadia] In 2000 a decision of the Supreme Court of Canada obliged the provincial government to build French schools at least in Charlottetown and Summerside, the two largest communities.
[src:americas/acadia] The new French-language daily newspaper L'Acadie Nouvelle published in Caraquet appeared in 1984, replacing L’Évangeline which ceased publication in 1982.
[src:americas/acadia] The series of Acadian National Conventions from 1881 to 1972 was followed by an Acadian National Orientation Convention in 1979 at Edmundston.
[src:americas/acadia] Since 1994, there has been a new series of Acadian World Congresses at five-year intervals starting with 1994 in southeastern New Brunswick and 1999 in Louisiana.
[src:americas/acadia] The most recent was centered in Summerside, Prince Edward Island in 2019.
[src:americas/acadia] During much of the 17th and early 18th centuries, Norridgewock on the Kennebec River and Castine at the end of the Penobscot River were the southernmost settlements of Acadia.
[src:americas/acadia] The French government defined the borders of Acadia as roughly between the 40th and 46th parallels on the Atlantic coast.
[src:americas/acadia] The following list includes those who were born in Acadia (yet not necessarily of Acadian ethnicity) or those who became naturalized citizens prior to the fall of the French in the region in 1763.
[src:americas/acadia] Those who came for brief periods from other countries are not included (e.g.
[src:americas/acadia] John Gorham, Edward Cornwallis, James Wolfe, Boishébert, etc.).
[src:americas/acadia] Acadia was in territory disputed between France and Great Britain.
[src:americas/acadia] Although France controlled the territory in the remaining periods, French monarchs consistently neglected Acadia.
[src:americas/acadia] Civil government under the French regime was held by a series of Governors (see List of governors of Acadia).
[src:americas/acadia] The government of New France was in Quebec, but it had only nominal authority over the Acadians.
[src:americas/acadia] The Acadians implemented village self-rule.
[src:americas/acadia] Even after Canada had given up its elected spokesmen, the Acadians continued to demand a say in their own government, as late as 1706 petitioning the monarchy to allow them to elect spokesmen each year by a plurality of voices.
[src:americas/acadia] In a sign of his indifference to the colony, Louis XV agreed to their demand.
[src:americas/acadia] This representative assembly was a direct offshoot of a government system that developed out of the seigneurial and church parish imported from Europe.
[src:americas/acadia] The seigneurial system was a "set of legal regimes and practices pertaining to local landholding, politics, economics, and jurisprudence." Many of the French governors of Acadia prior to Hector d'Andigné de Grandfontaine held seigneuries in Acadia.
[src:americas/acadia] As Seigneur, in addition to the power held as governor, they held the right to grant land, collect their seigneurial rents, and act in judgement over disputes within their domain.
[src:americas/acadia] After Acadia came under direct Royal rule under Grandfontaine the Seigneurs continued to fulfill governance roles.
[src:americas/acadia] The Acadian seignuerial system came to an end when the British Crown bought the seigneurial rights in the 1730s.
[src:americas/acadia] The Catholic parish system along with the accompanying parish priest also aided in the development Acadian self-government.
[src:americas/acadia] Priests, given their respected position, often assisted the community in representation with the civil government at Port Royal/Annapolis Royal.
[src:americas/acadia] Within each parish the Acadians used the elected *marguilliers* (wardens) of the *conseil de fabrique* to administer more than just the churches' affairs in the parishes.
[src:americas/acadia] The Acadians extended this system to see to the administrative needs of the community in general.
[src:americas/acadia] The Acadians occupied a borderland region of the British and French empires.
[src:americas/acadia] As such the Acadian homeland was subjected to the ravages of war on numerous occasions.
[src:americas/acadia] Through experience the Acadians learned to distrust imperial authorities (British and French).
[src:americas/acadia] This is evidenced in a small way when Acadians were uncooperative with census takers.
[src:americas/acadia] Administrators complained of constant in-fighting among the population, which filed many petty civil suits with colonial magistrates.
[src:americas/acadia] Most of these were over boundary lines, as the Acadians were very quick to protect their new lands.
[src:americas/acadia] After 1710, the British military administration continued to utilize the deputy system the Acadians had developed under French colonial rule.
[src:americas/acadia] Prior to 1732 the deputies were appointed by the governor from men in the districts of Acadian families "as ancientest and most considerable in Lands & possessions,".
[src:americas/acadia] This appears to be in contravention of various British penal laws which made it nearly impossible for Roman Catholics and Protestant recusants to hold military and government positions.
[src:americas/acadia] The need for effective administration and communication in many of the British colonies trumped the laws.
[src:americas/acadia] In 1732, the governance institution was formalized.
[src:americas/acadia] Under the formalized system the colony was divided into eight districts.
[src:americas/acadia] Annually on October 11 free elections were to take place where each district, depending on its size, was to elect two, three, or four deputies.
[src:americas/acadia] In observance of the Lord's Day, if October 11 fell on a Sunday the elections were to take place on the immediately following Monday.
[src:americas/acadia] Notice of the annual election was to be given in all districts thirty days before the election date.
[src:americas/acadia] Immediately following election, deputies, both outgoing and incoming, were to report to Annapolis Royal to receive the governor's approval and instructions.
[src:americas/acadia] Prior to 1732 deputies had complained about the time and expense of holding office and carrying out their duties.
[src:americas/acadia] Under the new elected deputy system each district was to provide for the expenses of their elected deputies.
[src:americas/acadia] In addition to deputies, several other public positions existed.
[src:americas/acadia] Each district had a clerk who worked closely with the deputies and under his duties recorded the records and orders of government, deeds and conveyances, and kept other public records.
[src:americas/acadia] With the rapid expansion of the Acadian populace, there was also a growing number of cattle and sheep.
[src:americas/acadia] The burgeoning herds and flocks, often free-ranging, necessitated the creation of the position of Overseer of Flocks.
[src:americas/acadia] These individuals controlled where the flocks grazed, settled disputes and recorded the names of individuals slaughtering animals to ensure proper ownership.
[src:americas/acadia] Skins and hides were inspected for brands.
[src:americas/acadia] After the purchase by the British Crown of the seigniorial rights in Acadia, various rents and fees were due to the Crown.
[src:americas/acadia] In the Minas, Piziquid and Cobequid Districts the seigniorial fees were collected by the "Collector & Receiver of All His Majesty's Quit Rents, Dues, or Revenues".
[src:americas/acadia] The Collector was to keep a record of all rents and other fees collected, submit the rents to Annapolis Royal, and retain fifteen percent to cover his expenses.
[src:americas/acadia] Before 1654, trading companies and patent holders concerned with fishing recruited men in France to come to Acadia to work at the commercial outposts.
[src:americas/acadia] The original Acadian population was a small number of indentured servants and soldiers brought by the fur-trading companies.
[src:americas/acadia] Gradually, fishermen began settling in the area as well, rather than return to France with the seasonal fishing fleet.
[src:americas/acadia] The majority of the recruiting took place at La Rochelle.
[src:americas/acadia] Between 1653 and 1654, 104 men were recruited at La Rochelle.
[src:americas/acadia] Of these, 31% were builders, 15% were soldiers and sailors, 8% were food preparers, 6.7% were farm workers, and an additional 6.7% worked in the clothing trades.
[src:americas/acadia] Fifty-five percent of Acadia's first families came from western and southwestern France, primarily from Poitou, Aquitaine, Angoumois, and Saintonge.
[src:americas/acadia] Over 85% of these (47% of the total), were former residents of the La Chaussée area of Poitou.
[src:americas/acadia] Many of the families who arrived in 1632 with Isaac de Razilly shared some blood ties; those not related by blood shared cultural ties with the others.
[src:americas/acadia] The number of original immigrants was very small, and only about 100 surnames existed within the Acadian community.
[src:americas/acadia] Many of the earliest French settlers in Acadia intermarried with the local Mi'kmaq tribe.
[src:americas/acadia] A Parisian lawyer, Marc Lescarbot, who spent just over a year in Acadia, arriving in May 1606, described the Micmac as having "courage, fidelity, generosity, and humanity, and their hospitality is so innate and praiseworthy that they receive among them every man who is not an enemy.
[src:americas/acadia] Most of the immigrants to Acadia were poor peasants in France, making them social equals in this new context.
[src:americas/acadia] Unlike the French colonists in Canada and the early English colonies in Plymouth and Jamestown, Acadians maintained an extended kinship system, and the large extended families assisted in building homes and barns, as well as cultivating and harvesting crops.
[src:americas/acadia] They also relied on interfamily cooperation to accomplish community goals, such as building dikes to reclaim tidal marshes.
[src:americas/acadia] Marriages were generally not love matches but were arranged for economic or social reasons.
[src:americas/acadia] Parental consent was required for anyone under 25 who wished to marry, and both the mother's and father's consent was recorded in the marriage deed.
[src:americas/acadia] Divorce was not permitted in New France, and annulments were almost impossible to get.
[src:americas/acadia] Legal separation was offered as an option but was seldom used.
[src:americas/acadia] The Acadians were suspicious of outsiders and on occasion did not readily cooperate with census takers.
[src:americas/acadia] The first reliable population figures for the area came with the census of 1671, which noted fewer than 450 people.
[src:americas/acadia] By 1714, the Acadian population had expanded to 2,528 individuals, mostly from natural increase rather than immigration.
[src:americas/acadia] Most Acadian women in the 18th century gave birth to living children an average of eleven times.
[src:americas/acadia] Although these numbers are identical to those in Canada, 75% of Acadian children reached adulthood, many more than in other parts of New France.
[src:americas/acadia] The isolation of the Acadian communities meant the people were not exposed to many of the imported epidemics, allowing the children to remain healthier.
[src:americas/acadia] In 1714, a few Acadian families emigrated to Île Royale.
[src:americas/acadia] But for the majority of Acadians, they could not be enticed by the French government to abandon their family lands for an area which was unknown and uncultivated.
[src:americas/acadia] Some Acadians migrated to nearby Île Saint-Jean (now Prince Edward Island) to take advantage of the fertile cropland.
[src:americas/acadia] In 1732, the island had 347 settlers but within 25 years its population had expanded to 5000 Europeans.
[src:americas/acadia] Much of the population surge on Île Saint-Jean took place in the 1750s, as Acadians left during the rising tensions on peninsular Nova Scotia after the settlement of Halifax in 1749.
[src:americas/acadia] Le Loutre played a role in these removals through acts of encouragement and threats.
[src:americas/acadia] The exodus to Île Saint-Jean became a flood with refugees fleeing British-held territory after the initial expulsions of 1755.
[src:americas/acadia] In contemporary Atlantic Canada, it is estimated that there are 300,000 French-speaking Acadians.
[src:americas/acadia] In addition, there is a diaspora of over three million Acadian descendants in the world, primarily in the United States, in Canada outside the Atlantic region, and in France.
[src:americas/acadia] Most Acadian households were self-sufficient, with families engaged in subsistence farming only for a few years while they established their farms.
[src:americas/acadia] Very rapidly the Acadians established productive farms that yielded surplus crops that allowed them to trade with both Boston and Louisbourg.
[src:americas/acadia] Farms tended to remain small plots of land worked by individual families rather than slave labor.
[src:americas/acadia] The highly productive dyked marshlands and cleared uplands produced an abundance of fodder that supported significant production of cows, sheep and pigs.
[src:americas/acadia] Farmers grew various grains: wheat, oats, barley, hops and rye; vegetables: peas, cabbage, turnips, onions, carrots, chives, shallots, asparagus, parsnips and beets; fruit: apples, pears, cherries, plums, raspberry and white strawberry.
[src:americas/acadia] In addition they grew crops of hemp and flax for the production of cloth, rope, etc.
[src:americas/acadia] From the rivers, estuaries and seas they harvested shad, smelts, gaspereau, cod, salmon, bass, etc., utilizing fish traps in the rivers, weirs in the inter-tidal zone and from the sea with lines and nets from their boats.
[src:americas/acadia] Charles Morris observed the Acadians at Minas hunting beluga whales.
[src:americas/acadia] The Acadians also varied their diets by hunting for moose, hare, ducks and geese, and pigeon.
[src:americas/acadia] After 1630, the Acadians began to build dikes and drain the sea marsh above Port Royal.
[src:americas/acadia] The high salinity of the reclaimed coastal marshland meant that the land would need to sit for three years after it was drained before it could be cultivated.
[src:americas/acadia] The land reclamation techniques that were used closely resembled the enclosures near La Rochelle that helped make solar salt.
[src:americas/acadia] As time progressed, the Acadian agriculture improved, and Acadians traded with the British colonies in New England to gain ironware, fine cloth, rum, and salt.
[src:americas/acadia] During the French administration of Acadia, this trade was illegal, but it did not stop some English traders from establishing small stores in Port Royal.
[src:americas/acadia] Under English rule, the Acadians traded with New England and often smuggled their excess food to Boston merchants waiting at Baie Verte for transshipment to the French at Louisbourg on Cape Breton Island.
[src:americas/acadia] Many adult sons who did not inherit land from their parents settled on adjacent vacant lands to remain close to their families.
[src:americas/acadia] As the Acadian population expanded and available land became limited around Port Royal, new settlements took root to the northeast, in the Upper Bay of Fundy, including Mines, Pisiquid, and Beaubassin.
[src:americas/acadia] Many of the pioneers into that area persuaded some of their relatives to accompany them, and most of the frontier settlements contained only five to ten interrelated family units.
[src:americas/aconcagua] The mountain lies 112 kilometres (70 mi) northwest of Mendoza, approximately 15 kilometres (9.3 mi) from the Argentine–Chilean border.
[src:americas/aconcagua] It is bounded by the Vacas Valley to the north and east and the Horcones Inferior Valley to the west and south, and is protected within Aconcagua Provincial Park.
[src:americas/aconcagua] Several glaciers descend its flanks, the largest being the Horcones Inferior glacier (*Ventisquero Horcones Inferior*), at roughly 10 kilometres (6.2 mi) long.
[src:americas/aconcagua] Aconcagua was formed by the subduction of the Nazca Plate beneath the South American Plate and was once an active stratovolcano, before tectonic shifts during the Miocene halted volcanic activity.
[src:americas/aconcagua] The first recorded ascent was made on 14 January 1897 by Swiss guide Matthias Zurbriggen, as part of a British expedition led by Edward FitzGerald.
[src:americas/aconcagua] From the north via the normal route, Aconcagua is considered technically straightforward and is often described as the highest non-technical mountain in the world, requiring no ropes or specialized equipment.
[src:americas/aconcagua] Nevertheless, the extreme altitude—where atmospheric pressure is roughly 40% of sea level—means altitude sickness affects most climbers, and the mountain records approximately three deaths per year, earning it the nickname "Mountain of Death." Summit success rates are estimated at 30–40%.
[src:americas/aconcagua] It may be from the Mapudungun *Aconca-Hue*, which refers to the Aconcagua River and means "comes from the other side"; the Quechua *Ackon Cahuak*, meaning "Sentinel of Stone"; the Quechua *Anco Cahuac*, meaning "White Sentinel"; or the Aymara *Janq'u Q'awa*, meaning "White Ravine".
[src:americas/aconcagua] The mountain was created by the subduction of the Nazca Plate beneath the South American Plate.
[src:americas/aconcagua] Aconcagua used to be an active stratovolcano (from the Late Cretaceous or Early Paleocene through the Miocene) and consisted of several volcanic complexes on the edge of a basin with a shallow sea.
[src:americas/aconcagua] However, sometime in the Miocene, about 8 to 10 million years ago, the subduction angle started to decrease, resulting in a stop of the melting and more horizontal stresses between the oceanic plate and the continent, causing the thrust faults that lifted Aconcagua off its volcanic root.
[src:americas/aconcagua] Volcanic activity ceased a long time ago.
[src:americas/aconcagua] The rocks on Aconcagua's flanks are all volcanic and consist of lavas, breccias and pyroclastics.
[src:americas/aconcagua] The shallow marine basin had already formed earlier (Triassic), even before Aconcagua arose as a volcano.
[src:americas/aconcagua] However, volcanism has been present in this region for as long as this basin was around and volcanic deposits interfinger with marine deposits throughout the sequence.
[src:americas/aconcagua] The colorful greenish, bluish and grey deposits seen in the Horcones Valley and south of Puente Del Inca, are carbonates, limestones, turbidites and evaporates that filled this basin.
[src:americas/aconcagua] The red-colored rocks are intrusions, cinder deposits and conglomerates of volcanic origin.
[src:americas/aconcagua] In mountaineering terms, Aconcagua is technically an easy mountain if approached from the north, via the normal route.
[src:americas/aconcagua] Aconcagua is arguably the highest *non-technical* mountain in the world since the northern route does not absolutely require ropes, axes, and pins.
[src:americas/aconcagua] Although the effects of altitude are severe (atmospheric pressure is 40% of sea level at the summit), the use of supplemental oxygen is not common.
[src:americas/aconcagua] Altitude sickness will affect most climbers to some extent, depending on the degree of acclimatization.
[src:americas/aconcagua] Although the normal climb is technically easy, multiple casualties occur every year on this mountain (in January 2009 alone, five climbers died).
[src:americas/aconcagua] This is due to the large numbers of climbers who attempt the ascent and because many climbers underestimate the significant risk posed by the elevation and cold weather.
[src:americas/aconcagua] Given the weather conditions close to the summit, hypothermia is very common.
[src:americas/aconcagua] The routes to the peak from the south and south-west ridges are more demanding and the south face climb is considered quite difficult.
[src:americas/aconcagua] The Polish Glacier Traverse route, also known as the "Falso de los Polacos" route, crosses through the Vacas valley, ascends to the base of the Polish Glacier, then traverses across to the normal route for the final ascent to the summit.
[src:americas/aconcagua] The third most popular route is by the Polish Glacier itself.
[src:americas/aconcagua] Provincial Park rangers do not maintain records of successful summits but estimates suggest a summit rate of 30–40%.
[src:americas/aconcagua] About 75% of climbers are foreigners and 25% are Argentinean.
[src:americas/aconcagua] Among foreigners, the United States leads in the number of climbers, followed by Germany and the United Kingdom.
[src:americas/aconcagua] About 54% of climbers ascend the Normal Route, 43% up the Polish Glacier Traverse Route, and the remaining 3% on other routes.
[src:americas/aconcagua] The campsites on the normal route are listed below (elevations are approximate).
[src:americas/aconcagua] Summit attempts are usually made from a high camp at either Berlín or Colera, or from the lower camp at Nido de Cóndores.
[src:americas/aconcagua] The first attempt to summit Aconcagua by Europeans was made in 1883 by a party led by the German geologist and explorer Paul Güssfeldt.
[src:americas/aconcagua] Bribing porters with the story of treasure on the mountain, he approached the mountain via the Rio Volcan, making two attempts on the peak by the northwest ridge and reaching an elevation of 6,500 metres (21,300 ft).
[src:americas/aconcagua] The route that he prospected is now the standard route up the mountain.
[src:americas/aconcagua] The first recorded ascent was in 1897 by a European expedition led by the British mountaineer Edward FitzGerald.
[src:americas/aconcagua] FitzGerald failed to reach the summit himself over eight attempts between December 1896 and February 1897, but the (Swiss) guide of the expedition, Matthias Zurbriggen reached the summit on 14 January.
[src:americas/aconcagua] On the final attempt a month later, two other expedition members, Stuart Vines and Nicola Lanti, reached the summit on 13 February.
[src:americas/aconcagua] The east side of Aconcagua was first scaled by a Polish expedition, with Konstanty Narkiewicz-Jodko, Stefan Daszyński, Wiktor Ostrowski and Stefan Osiecki summiting on 8 March 1934, over what is now known as the *Polish Glacier*.
[src:americas/aconcagua] A route over the Southwest Ridge was pioneered over seven days in January 1953 by the Swiss-Argentine team of Frederico and Dorly Marmillod, Francisco Ibanez and Fernando Grajales.
[src:americas/aconcagua] The famously difficult South Face was conquered by a French team led by René Ferlet.
[src:americas/aconcagua] Pierre Lesueur, Adrien Dagory, Robert Paragot, Edmond Denis, Lucien Berardini and Guy Poulet reached the summit after a month of effort on 25 February 1954.
[src:americas/aconcagua] As of 2020 the youngest person to reach the summit of Aconcagua is Tyler Armstrong of California.
[src:americas/aconcagua] He was nine years old when he reached the summit on 24 December 2013.
[src:americas/aconcagua] Kaamya Karthikeyan of India at an age of 12 became the youngest girl to reach the summit on 1 February 2020.
[src:americas/aconcagua] The oldest person to climb it was Scott Lewis, who reached the summit on 26 November 2007, when he was 87 years old.
[src:americas/aconcagua] In the base camp Plaza de Mulas (at 4,300 m (14,100 ft) above sea level) there is the highest contemporary art gallery tent called "Nautilus" of the Argentine painter Miguel Doura.
[src:americas/aconcagua] In 2014, Kilian Jornet set a record for climbing and descending Aconcagua from Horcones in 12 hours and 49 minutes.
[src:americas/aconcagua] The record was broken less than two months later by Ecuadorian-Swiss Karl Egloff, in a time of 11 hours 52 minutes, nearly an hour faster than Kilian Jornet.
[src:americas/aconcagua] This record was broken by American Tyler Andrews in 2023, with a time of 11 hours and 24 minutes.
[src:americas/aconcagua] In 2016, Fernanda Maciel set the first women's record for climbing and descending Aconcagua from Horcones in 22 hours, 52 minutes.
[src:americas/aconcagua] The current women's record is held by Ecuadorean Daniela Sandoval at 20 hours, 17 minutes.
[src:americas/aconcagua] On January 23, 2019 the Cholita climbers were the first Indigenous, Aymara women to climb the mountain in traditional clothing.
[src:americas/aconcagua] Their climb was sponsored by the Ministry of Culture and Tourism of Bolivia and the expedition is now detailed in a documentary film called 'Cholitas'.
[src:americas/aconcagua] On 25 September 2019, an Airbus Helicopters H145 landed on the very peak of Mount Aconcagua.
[src:americas/aconcagua] This is the first time in history a twin-engine helicopter has landed at this altitude.
[src:americas/aconcagua] It took a total of 45 minutes for the entire trip, 30 minutes from Mendoza and another 15 from the base camp up to the peak.
[src:americas/aconcagua] Temperatures were reported as low as −22 °C (−8 °F), with wind gusts up to 30 kn (56 km/h; 35 mph).
[src:americas/aconcagua] This is not the highest a helicopter has landed before, as a single-engine Airbus Helicopters H125 landed on Mount Everest, the highest mountain in the world.
[src:americas/aconcagua] At nearly 7,000 m (23,000 ft), Aconcagua is the highest peak outside Asia.
[src:americas/aconcagua] It is believed to have the highest death rate of any mountain in South America — around three a year — which has earned it the nickname "Mountain of Death".
[src:americas/aconcagua] More than 100 people have died on Aconcagua since records began.
[src:americas/aconcagua] Due to the improper disposal of human waste in the mountain environment there are significant health hazards that pose a threat to both animals and human beings.
[src:americas/aconcagua] Only boiled or chemically treated water is acceptable for drinking.
[src:americas/aconcagua] Additionally, ecofriendly toilets are available only to members of an organized expedition, meaning climbers have to "be contracted to a toilet service" at the base camp and similar camps along the route.
[src:americas/aconcagua] As of 2015, from two base camps (Plaza de Mulas and Plaza Argentina), over 120 barrels of waste (approx.
[src:americas/aconcagua] 22,500 kg (49,600 lb)) are flown out by helicopter each season.
[src:americas/aconcagua] In addition, individual mountaineers must make a payment before using these toilets.
[src:americas/aconcagua] Some large organizers will charge up to US$ 100, while smaller ones may charge US$ 5 per day or US$ 10 for the entire stay; thus, many independent mountaineers choose to defecate on the mountainside.
[src:americas/aconcagua] For the Incas, Aconcagua was a sacred mountain.
[src:americas/aconcagua] Ampato), places of worship were built here and sacrifices, including human sacrifices, were made.
[src:americas/aconcagua] The sites discovered in 1985 at an elevation of 5167 m are among the highest in the world and are the most difficult of all Inca sites to reach.
[src:americas/aconcagua] Here, the remains of a child bedded on grass, cloth and feathers were found inside stone walls (Aconcagua mummy).
[src:americas/aconcagua] The clothing indicates that the child was a member of the highest social class.
[src:americas/aconcagua] Other offerings found included figures and coca leaves.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] The **Adams–Onís Treaty** was an agreement between Spain and the United States, signed February 22, 1819, by John Quincy Adams and Luis de Onís respectively.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] The US acquired Florida while renouncing claims to Spanish Texas and establishing its first transcontinental boundary.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] The provisions of the treaty remained in full effect only until August 24, 1821, when the Treaty of Córdoba acknowledged Mexican independence from Spain.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] In the 1828 Treaty of Limits (Mexico–United States), the border defined by the Adams–Onís Treaty was recognized as the boundary between Mexico and the US, although following the 1845 Texas annexation, it was amended again by the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] The Adams–Onís Treaty was formally terminated in 1902.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] Pinckney's Treaty of 1795 established borders between the United States and Spanish Florida, but expansion by American settlers into this region led to ongoing disputes between the countries.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] The 1803 Louisiana Purchase caused further arguments over whether the new boundary to the south ran along the Sabine River, or the Rio Grande.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] The outbreak of the Peninsular War in 1807 and the Spanish American wars of independence in 1808, undermined Madrid's ability to retain its American territories.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] Between 1810 and 1813, the US took advantage to annex West Florida in piecemeal fashion from the Mississippi east to the Perdido River, the modern state boundary with Alabama.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] During the first of the Seminole Wars from 1817 to 1818, the US occupied the rest of Florida, presenting John Quincy Adams, then Secretary of State, an opportunity to negotiate favorable terms.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] His policy was to simultaneously avoid foreign commitments, but to also establish the US as the preponderant power on the North American continent.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] This required the elimination as far as possible of competing Spanish, Russian and British interests in the region, and extending the limits of American power to the Pacific.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] These principles were set out in more detail in the 1823 Monroe Doctrine.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] By 1819, Spain was prepared to accept the loss of Florida in exchange for a firm border in Texas.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] For his part, Adams saw an opportunity to remove outstanding Spanish claims in the Western United States, and establish the US' first transcontinental boundary.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] Despite their increasingly tenuous position in New Spain, the Madrid government was prepared to make concessions, hoping to regain them at a later date.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] Negotiations were held in Washington, D.C., led by Adams for the United States, and Luis de Onís, the Spanish ambassador, resulting in a final agreement of 16 articles.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] Key provisions included Article 2, transferring East and West Florida to the US, and Article 3, defining the southern border between the two countries, while Spain withdrew historic claims to the Oregon Country.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] Other terms included an agreement by the US government to compensate American settlers for alleged losses inflicted by the Spanish, the continuation of Pinckney's Treaty, and most favoured nation privileges for Spanish traders in Pensacola and St.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] Senate approved the treaty unanimously on February 24, 1819, but Madrid delayed ratification until October 1820, hoping to dissuade the US from supporting anti-Spanish revolutionaries.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] As a result of the delay, the Senate had to vote a second time, at which point Henry Clay and others demanded the cession of Texas in addition.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] This proposal was defeated and the treaty officially made effective on February 22, 1821.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] In accordance with Article 11, the US government set up a commission to handle claims made by private American citizens against Spain, which distributed around $5 million prior to its dissolution in 1824.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] For the United States, this Treaty (and the Treaty of 1818 with Britain agreeing to joint control of the Pacific Northwest) meant that its claimed territory now extended far west from the Mississippi River to the Pacific Ocean.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] For Spain, it meant that it kept its colony of Texas and also kept a buffer zone between its colonies in California and New Mexico and the U.S. territories.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] Many historians consider the Treaty to be a great achievement for the U.S., as time validated Adams's vision that it would allow the U.S. to open trade with the Orient across the Pacific.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] Informally this new border has been called the "Step Boundary", although the step-like shape of the boundary was not apparent for several decades—the source of the Arkansas, believed to be near the 42nd parallel north, was not known until John C.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] Frémont located it in the 1840s, hundreds of miles south of the 42nd parallel.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] Spain finally recognized the independence of Mexico with the Treaty of Córdoba signed on August 24, 1821.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] While Mexico was not initially a party to the Adams–Onís Treaty, in 1831 Mexico ratified the treaty by agreeing to the 1828 Treaty of Limits with the U.S.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] With the Russo-American Treaty of 1824, the Russian Empire ceded its claims south of parallel 54°40′ north to the United States.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] With the Treaty of Saint Petersburg in 1825, Russia set the southern border of Alaska on the same parallel in exchange for the Russian right to trade south of that border and the British right to navigate north of that border.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] This set the absolute limits of the Oregon Country/Columbia District between the 42nd parallel north and the parallel 54°40′ north west of the Continental Divide.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] By the mid-1830s, a controversy developed regarding the border with Texas, during which the United States demonstrated that the Sabine and Neches rivers had been switched on maps, moving the frontier in favor of Mexico.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] As a consequence, the eastern boundary of Texas was not firmly established until the independence of the Republic of Texas in 1836.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] It was not agreed upon by the United States and Mexico until the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo in 1848, which concluded the Mexican–American War.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] That treaty also formalized the cession by Mexico of Alta California and today's American Southwest, except for the territory of the later Gadsden Purchase of 1854.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] Another dispute occurred after Texas joined the Union.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] The treaty stated that the boundary between the French claims on the north and the Spanish claims on the south was Rio Roxo de Natchitoches (Red River) until it reached the 100th meridian, as noted on the John Melish map of 1818.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] But, the 100th meridian on the Melish map was marked some 90 miles (140 km) east of the true 100th meridian, and the Red River forked about 50 miles (80 km) east of the 100th meridian.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] Texas claimed the land south of the North Fork, and the United States claimed the land north of the South Fork (later called the Prairie Dog Town Fork Red River).
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] In 1860, Texas organized the area as Greer County.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] The matter was not settled until a United States Supreme Court ruling in 1896 upheld federal claims to the territory, after which it was added to the Oklahoma Territory.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] The treaty gave rise to a later border dispute between the states of Oregon and California, which remains unresolved.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] Upon statehood in 1850, California established the 42nd parallel as its constitutional de jure border as it had existed since 1819 when the territory was part of Spanish Mexico.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] In an 1868–1870 border survey following the admission of Oregon as a state, errors were made in demarcating and marking the Oregon-California border, creating a dispute that continues to this day.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] In 2020, a hoax appeared in Spain according to which, in 2055, the Adams–Onís Treaty would expire and Florida would be returned to Spain by the United States, which is false.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] The previous Anglo-American Convention of 1818 meant that both American and British citizens could settle land north of the 42nd parallel and west of the Continental Divide.
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] The United States now had a firm foothold on the Pacific Coast and could commence settlement of the jointly occupied Oregon Country (known as the Columbia District to the British government).
[src:americas/adams-onís-treaty] The Russian Empire also claimed this entire region as part of Russian America.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Africa straddles the equator and the prime meridian.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The continent is surrounded by the Mediterranean Sea to the north, the Arabian plate and the Gulf of Aqaba to the northeast, the Indian Ocean to the southeast and the Atlantic Ocean to the west.
[src:americas/africa-p01] France, Italy, Portugal, Spain, and Yemen have parts of their territories located on African geographical soil, mostly in the form of islands.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The continent includes Madagascar and various archipelagos.
[src:americas/africa-p01] It contains 54 fully recognised sovereign states, eight cities and islands that are part of non-African states, and two *de facto* independent states with limited or no recognition.
[src:americas/africa-p01] This count does not include Malta and Sicily, which are geologically part of the African continent.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Algeria is Africa's largest country by area, and Nigeria is its largest by population.
[src:americas/africa-p01] African nations cooperate through the establishment of the African Union, which is headquartered in Addis Ababa.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Africa is highly biodiverse; it is the continent with the largest number of megafauna species, as it was least affected by the extinction of the Pleistocene megafauna.
[src:americas/africa-p01] However, Africa is also heavily affected by a wide range of environmental issues, including desertification, deforestation, water scarcity, and pollution.
[src:americas/africa-p01] These entrenched environmental concerns are expected to worsen as climate change impacts Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The UN Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change has identified Africa as the continent most vulnerable to climate change.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The history of Africa is long, complex, and varied, and has often been under-appreciated by the global historical community.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In African societies the oral word is revered, and they have generally recorded their history via oral tradition, which has led anthropologists to term them "oral civilisations", contrasted with "literate civilisations" which pride the written word.
[src:americas/africa-p01] African culture is rich and diverse both within and between the continent's regions, encompassing art, cuisine, music and dance, religion, and dress.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Africa, particularly Eastern Africa, is widely accepted to be the place of origin of humans and the Hominidae clade, also known as the great apes.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The earliest hominids and their ancestors have been dated to around 7 million years ago, and *Homo sapiens* (modern human) are believed to have originated in Africa 350,000 to 260,000 years ago.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Throughout history the continent saw the rise and fall of many kingdoms and empires, such as Ancient Egypt, Makuria, the Fatimids, Mali, the Asante, Kongo, the Luba, Bunyoro, Great Zimbabwe, Imerina, and the Zulu.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Despite the predominance of states, many societies were heterarchical and stateless.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Slave trades created various diasporas, especially in the Americas.
[src:americas/africa-p01] From the late-19th century to early 20th century, driven by the Second Industrial Revolution, most of Africa was rapidly conquered and colonised by European nations, save for Ethiopia and Liberia.
[src:americas/africa-p01] European rule had significant impacts on Africa's societies, and colonies were maintained for the purpose of economic exploitation and extraction of natural resources.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Most present states emerged from a process of decolonisation following World War II, and established the Organisation of African Unity in 1963, the predecessor to the African Union.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The nascent countries decided to keep their colonial borders, with traditional power structures used in governance to varying degrees.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Under Roman rule, Carthage became the capital of the province then named *Africa Proconsularis*, following the Roman victory over the Carthaginians in the Third Punic War in 146 BC, which also included the coastal part of modern Libya.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The Latin suffix *-ica* can sometimes be used to denote a land (e.g., in *Celtica* from *Celtae*, as used by Julius Caesar).
[src:americas/africa-p01] The later Muslim region of Ifriqiya, following its conquest of the Byzantine (Eastern Roman) Empire's *Exarchatus Africae*, also preserved a form of the name.
[src:americas/africa-p01] According to the Romans, Africa lies to the west of Egypt, while "Asia" was used to refer to Anatolia and lands to the east.
[src:americas/africa-p01] A definite line was drawn between the two continents by the geographer Ptolemy (85–165 CE), indicating Alexandria along the Prime Meridian and making the isthmus of Suez and the Red Sea the boundary between Asia and Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p01] As Europeans came to understand the real extent of the continent, the idea of "Africa" expanded with their knowledge.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In accordance with African cosmology, African historical consciousness viewed historical change and continuity, order and purpose within the framework of man and his environment, the gods, and his ancestors, and he believed himself part of a holistic spiritual entity.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In African societies, the historical process is largely a communal one, with eyewitness accounts, hearsay, reminiscences, and occasionally visions, dreams, and hallucinations crafted into narrative oral traditions which are performed and transmitted through generations.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In oral traditions time is sometimes mythical and social, and ancestors were considered historical actors.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Mind and memory shapes traditions, as events are condensed over time and crystallise into clichés.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Oral tradition can be exoteric or esoteric.
[src:americas/africa-p01] It speaks to people according to their understanding, unveiling itself in accordance with their aptitudes.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Africa is considered by most paleoanthropologists to be the oldest inhabited territory on Earth, with the Human species originating from the continent.
[src:americas/africa-p01] During the mid-20th century, anthropologists discovered many fossils and evidence of human occupation perhaps as early as seven million years ago ("Before Present"; BP).
[src:americas/africa-p01] Fossil remains of several species of early apelike humans thought to have evolved into modern humans, such as *Australopithecus afarensis* radiometrically dated to approximately 3.9–3.0 million years BP, *Paranthropus boisei* (c.
[src:americas/africa-p01] 2.3–1.4 million years BP) and *Homo ergaster* (c.
[src:americas/africa-p01] 1.9 million–600,000 years BP) have been discovered.
[src:americas/africa-p01] After the evolution of *Homo sapiens* approximately 350,000 to 260,000 years BP in Africa, the continent was mainly populated by groups of hunter-gatherers.
[src:americas/africa-p01] These first modern humans left Africa and populated the rest of the globe during the Out of Africa II migration dated to approximately 50,000 years BP, exiting the continent either across Bab-el-Mandeb over the Red Sea, the Strait of Gibraltar in Morocco, or the Isthmus of Suez in Egypt.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Other migrations of modern humans within the African continent have been dated to that time, with evidence of early human settlement found in Southern Africa, Southeast Africa, North Africa, and the Sahara.
[src:americas/africa-p01] However, the warming and drying climate meant that by 5,000 BC, the Sahara region was becoming increasingly dry and hostile.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Around 3500 BC, due to a tilt in the Earth's orbit, the Sahara experienced a period of rapid desertification.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The domestication of cattle in Africa preceded agriculture and seems to have existed alongside hunter-gatherer cultures.
[src:americas/africa-p01] It is speculated that by 6,000 BC, cattle were domesticated in North Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In West Africa, a wet phase ushered in an expanding rainforest and wooded savanna from Senegal to Cameroon.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Between 9,000 and 5,000 BC, Niger–Congo speakers domesticated the oil palm and raffia palm.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Black-eyed peas and voandzeia (African groundnuts), were domesticated, followed by okra and kola nuts.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Since most of the plants grew in the forest, the Niger–Congo speakers invented polished stone axes for clearing forest.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Pygmies are thought to have inhabited Central Africa for many millennia, splitting into eastern and western groups around 5,000 BP.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Over 150,000 BP, there was an early dispersal of anatomically modern humans to Southern Africa, equated with the modern-day Khoisan who have preserved their traditional hunter-gatherer way of life.
[src:americas/africa-p01] From 3500 BC, nomes (ruled by nomarchs) coalesced to form the kingdoms of Lower Egypt and Upper Egypt in northeast Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Around 3100 BC Upper Egypt conquered Lower Egypt to unify Egypt under the 1st dynasty, with the process of consolidation and assimilation completed by the time of the 3rd dynasty who formed the Old Kingdom of Egypt in 2686 BC.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The Kingdom of Kerma emerged around this time to become the dominant force in Nubia, controlling territory as large as Egypt between the 1st and 4th cataracts of the Nile.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The height of the Old Kingdom saw the construction of many great pyramids, though under the 6th dynasty power gradually decentralised to the nomarchs, culminating in the disintegration of the kingdom, exacerbated by drought and famine.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Around 2055 BC, the 11th dynasty, based in Thebes, conquered the others to form the Middle Kingdom of Egypt, and the 12th dynasty expanded into Lower Nubia at the expense of Kerma.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Around 1700 BC, the Middle Kingdom fractured in two, and the Hyksos (a militaristic people from Palestine) invaded and conquered Lower Egypt, while Kerma coordinated invasions deep into Egypt to reach its greatest extent.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In 1550 BC, the 18th dynasty expelled the Hyksos, and established the New Kingdom of Egypt.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The New Kingdom conquered the Levant from the Canaanites, Mittani, Amorites, and Hittites, and extinguished Kerma, incorporating Nubia into the empire, and sending the Egyptian empire into its golden age.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Internal struggles, drought, famine, and invasions by a confederation of seafaring peoples contributed to the New Kingdom's collapse in 1069 BC.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The New Kingdom's collapse liberated the Kingdom of Kush in Nubia, which manoeuvred into power in Upper Egypt and conquered Lower Egypt in 754 BC to form the Kushite Empire.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The Kushites ruled for a century and oversaw a revival in pyramid building, until they were driven out of Egypt by the Assyrians in 663 BC in reprisal for their expansion towards the Assyrian Empire.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The Assyrians installed a puppet dynasty that later gained independence and once more unified Egypt, until it was conquered by the Achaemenid Empire in 525 BC.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Egypt briefly regained independence from the Achaemenids under the 28th dynasty from 404 to 343 BC.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The conquest of Achaemenid Egypt by Alexander the Great in 332 BC marked the beginning of Hellenistic rule and the installation of the Macedonian Ptolemaic dynasty in Egypt.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The Ptolemaics lost their holdings outside of Africa to the Seleucids in the Syrian Wars, expanded into Cyrenaica, and briefly occupied part of Kush in the 3rd century BC.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the 1st century BC, Ptolemaic Egypt became entangled in a Roman civil war, leading to its conquest by the Romans in 30 BC.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Kush persisted as a major regional power until, having been weakened from internal rebellion amid worsening climatic conditions, invasions by Aksum and the Noba caused their disintegration into Makuria, Alodia, and Nobatia around the 5th century AD.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the Horn of Africa, there was the Land of Punt, a kingdom on the Red Sea which was a close trading partner of Ancient Egypt in the 3rd and 2nd millennia BC.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Rodolfo Fattovich equated it to the Gash Group in the Sudanese-Eritrean lowlands, and some scholars have hypothesised modern-day Somalia, while Kenneth Kitchen and Felix Chami locate it on Zanzibar Island.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the Eritrean-Ethiopian Highlands, the kingdom of dʿmt rose c.
[src:americas/africa-p01] 980 BC as the region was incorporated into global trading networks, and it exhibited Sabaean influences which most scholars attribute to a small migration of Sabaeans and their assimilation.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Several scholars consider there to have been other contemporaneous states, and dʿmt's collapse in the mid-1st century BC saw the region inhabited by small polities.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Modern-day Somalia was inhabited by nomadic pastoralists, and along the Horn's coast there were many ancient Somali city-states that thrived off of the wider Red Sea trade, and enjoyed a lucrative monopoly on cinnamon from Ancient India due to their freedom from Roman interference.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the 1st century AD, the Kingdom of Aksum rose from a city-state to rule much of the northern Ethiopian-Eritrean Highlands and the Red Sea port of Adulis.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Aksum was described as one of the four great powers by Persian prophet Mani in the 3rd century.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Aksum's king converted from traditional religion to Christianity in the 4th century, gradually followed by the population.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the 6th century, Aksum conquered South Arabia, though struggled to maintain control over it, and began to gradually lose its dominance over Red Sea trade to Persians and Arabs.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Northwest Africa (the Maghreb) was inhabited by Berber semi-nomadic pastoralists.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the 1st millennium BC, Phoenician migration and settlement came in search for precious metals in the Gulf of Tunis.
[src:americas/africa-p01] This grew into Ancient Carthage after gaining independence from Phoenicia in the 6th century BC, and they built an extensive trading empire with a strict mercantile network.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Carthage's collapse and conquest by Rome in the Punic Wars (3rd and 2nd centuries BC) saw Numidia and Mauretania become major powers in the Maghreb.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Towards the end of the 2nd century BC Mauretania fought alongside Numidia's Jugurtha against the Romans in the Jugurthine War after he had usurped the Numidian throne from a Roman ally.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Together they inflicted heavy casualties, with the war only ending inconclusively when Mauretania's Bocchus I sold out Jugurtha to the Romans.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Around the turn of the millennium, both came under direct Roman rule.
[src:americas/africa-p01] While traditional religion predominated among Berbers, some people converted to Christianity.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the 5th century AD the Vandals conquered Roman Africa before the fall of Rome, though the province was reconquered by the Byzantines a century later.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Large swathes of indigenous peoples regained self-governance in Masuna and its numerous successor polities in the Maghreb, including the kingdoms of Ouarsenis, Aurès, and Altava.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the western Sahel the rise of settled communities occurred largely as a result of the domestication of millet and of sorghum, and cattle pastoralism began c.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Extensive east-west belts of deserts, grasslands, and forests from north to south were crucial for the moulding of their respective societies and meant that symbiotic trade relations developed in response to the differing environments.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Beginning around 4000 BC, the Tichitt culture in modern-day Mauritania and Mali is the oldest known complexly organised society in West Africa, while others included the Kintampo culture in modern-day Ghana, the Nok culture in modern-day Nigeria, and the Daima culture around Lake Chad.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Towards the end of the 3rd century AD, a wet period in the Sahel created areas for human habitation and exploitation that had not been habitable for the best part of a millennium.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The Ghana Empire (also called *Wagadu*) rose out of the Tichitt culture, growing wealthy following the introduction of the camel to the western Sahel, which revolutionised the trans-Saharan trade that linked their capital and Aoudaghost with Tahert and Sijilmasa in North Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Soninke tradition holds that the final founding of Wagadu occurred after Dinga did a deal with Bida, a serpent deity who was guarding a well, to sacrifice one maiden a year in exchange for assurance regarding plenty of rainfall and gold supply.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Based on large tumuli scattered across West Africa dating to this period, several scholars have speculated that there were further simultaneous and preceding states relative to Wagadu.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the Grasslands of northwestern Cameroon, Bantu-speaking agriculturalists started to gradually migrate south sometime between 5000 BC and 3000 BC.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Despite intensive research, the cause of the migrations, and that of the directions taken, is still unclear, however there is consensus that there were multiple dispersal events.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Around 1500 BC, Bantu speakers reached central Cameroon.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The 'Western Stream' likely followed the coast and the major rivers of the Congo system southwards to reach the southern fringe of the Congolian Rainforest around 500 BC (some may have used the sea to circumvent the rainforest).
[src:americas/africa-p01] Their arrival coincided with the spread of iron metallurgy through Central Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Meanwhile, the 'Eastern Stream' travelled either the northern fringe of the rainforest or the Ubangi River eastwards, and reached just west of Lake Victoria around 500 BC.
[src:americas/africa-p01] While there, Bantu speakers adopted iron metallurgy from Cushitic speakers already present, and coexisted with them.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Dispersal from the Great Lakes region occurred in two more streams.
[src:americas/africa-p01] One went west to meet the Western Stream in the DR Congo and Angola, while the other went south and spread across Eastern and Southern Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Around the turn of the millennium, Bantu speakers reached central modern-day Tanzania and near Dar es Salaam, before rapidly moving southwards along the coast to reach modern-day Kwazulu Natal in South Africa around the 3rd century AD.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Throughout this, Bantu speakers displaced, replaced, or intermarried with and absorbed hunter-gatherer and agricultural groups.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the 7th and 8th centuries, as part of the Arab conquests which sought to spread Islamic rule, the Rashidun and Umayyad caliphates conquered North Africa at the expense of the Byzantine Empire and Berber leaders such as Kusaila and Kahina.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Large numbers of Berber and Coptic people willingly converted to Islam, and followers of Abrahamic religions ('People of the Book') were protected, though followers of Berber traditional religion were violently oppressed.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the 8th century the Berber Revolt rocked the Caliphate and Berber dynasties took control over the Maghreb, while the Tulunids briefly controlled Egypt.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the 10th century, the Fatimids rose to power in modern-day Tunisia, established a rival caliphate, and conquered Egypt, before expanding into the Middle East.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the 11th century the Almoravids conquered the Maghreb and intervened in the Christian reconquest of Iberia.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Saladin, a Fatimid vizier, usurped power in the 12th century and established the Ayyubid dynasty which restored Egyptian prestige, while the Almohad revolution deposed the Almoravids to the east.
[src:americas/africa-p01] After Christian gains in Iberia in the 13th century, the Almohads disintegrated into the Marinids, Zayyanids, and Hafsids in modern-day Morocco, Algeria, and Tunisia respectively.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the face of Mongol expansion, Mamluk generals seized power in Egypt and expanded into the Middle East.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the early-16th century, the Ottoman Empire rapidly conquered North Africa (save for Morocco, now under Saadi rule) to counter Spanish expansionism.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the following centuries, over a million Europeans are estimated to have been captured and enslaved by Barbary corsairs.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The Ottoman regencies became more independent during the 18th century.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the central Sahel around Lake Chad, the Kanem–Bornu Empire ruled from the 6th century, and projected power over the Hausa Kingdoms.
[src:americas/africa-p01] To the east during 7th century, Makuria conquered Nobatia to become the dominant power in the region and resisted Muslim expansion.
[src:americas/africa-p01] They later entered a severe decline following civil war and Arab migrations to the Sudan and had disintegrated by the 15th century, giving rise to the Funj Sultanate.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The Tunjur empire's collapse in the central Sudan saw the rise of the Bagirmi, Wadai, and Darfur sultanates, which frequently raided the populations to their south for slaves.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the Horn of Africa, Aksum lost control of the Red Sea, and its isolation from Christendom caused Ethiopian society to introspect and take inspiration from the Old Testament.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Islamised Beja invaded the Ethiopian Highlands, forcing Aksum to migrate south, where, according to tradition, Aksum's expansion was met by a Jewish or traditionalist queen who destroyed the state c.
[src:americas/africa-p01] During the 13th century, hegemony in the Horn was contested by the Christian Zagwe, the Muslims of Shewa, and the traditionalist Damot; the Solomonic dynasty overthrew the Zagwe to found the Ethiopian Empire, while Shewa was replaced by Ifat.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Soon after, Ethiopia conquered Damot and the Muslim states, entering into a 'golden age'.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the 16th century Muslims united behind Adal in *jihad* to reconquer the Muslim lands and occupy Ethiopia, until, with Portuguese assistance, Ethiopia counter-attacked and its sovereignty was restored in a reduced state.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The 16th and 17th centuries also saw Oromo invasions into the Horn, weakening Ethiopia further and causing the collapse of Adal, while Ajuran on the east coast also disintegrated.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Ethiopia briefly consolidated its authority in the late-17th century, though the turn of the century saw fragmentation and gradually-increasing anarchy, which continued throughout the 18th century.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the Sahel region of West Africa, the Ghana Empire formed from between the 2nd and 8th centuries, while from the 7th century the Gao Empire ruled to its east.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Almoravid capture of royal Aoudaghost led to Ghana's conversion to Islam in the 11th century, and climatic changes led to Ghana's conquest by its vassal Sosso in the 13th century.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Sosso was quickly overthrown by the Mali Empire who conquered Gao and dominated the trans-Saharan trade.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The Mossi Kingdoms were established to its south.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The 15th century saw the crumbling of the Mali Empire, with the dominant power in the region becoming the Songhai Empire centered on Gao.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Weakened by internal conflict, in 1591 Gao was conquered by Morocco, and the political vacuum came to be filled by the Segou Empire and several other states.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The once lucrative trans-Saharan trade gradually lost its prominence to the coastal Atlantic trade with Europeans, and the following centuries saw many droughts, famines, and epidemics.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the forest regions of West Africa, various kingdoms and empires flourished, such as the Yoruba empires of Ife and Oyo, the Igbo Kingdom of Nri, the Edo Kingdom of Benin (famous for its art), the Dagomba Kingdom of Dagbon, and the Akan kingdoms of Bonoman and Adanse.
[src:americas/africa-p01] They came into contact with the Portuguese in the 15th century which saw the start of the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The Asante Empire was established in present-day Ghana.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Between 1515 and 1800, 8 million Africans were exported in the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the western Congo Basin by the 13th century there were three main confederations of states: the Seven Kingdoms, Mpemba, and one led by Vungu.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the 14th century the Kingdom of Kongo emerged and dominated the region, with the Tio Kingdom to its north and Mwene Muji to its northeast.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Over the course of the late-16th and 17th centuries, the Portuguese sought to conquer Ndongo (allied to Matamba) in the Angolan Wars; despite fierce resistance from Queen Nzinga, and brief occupation of Luanda by the Dutch (allied to Kongo), Portugal controlled most of Ndongo by the 1670s.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The late-17th century saw Kongo fragment between royal houses as several vassals broke away; by the time of Kongo's restoration in 1709, it had ceased being the dominant regional power.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Also during the 17th century, in the textile-producing northeast, the Boma, Yaka, and possibly the Kuba and Pende kingdoms broke away from Mwene Muji.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the eastern Congo Basin, farmers, fishermen, and hunters (often Pygmies) built symbiotic relations.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Jan Vansina wrote that in the southern savanna 'lords of the land' held priestly roles due to their special relationship with the spirits of the land, and held sway over multiple villages, effectively ruling embryonic kingdoms.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Accordingly, as lineages grew, authority was opportunistically absorbed or incorporated by force.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The centre of the Luba Empire is yet to undergo archaeological research, meaning knowledge about its rise is limited; its foundation is typically dated to the 14th/15th centuries, though scholarly estimates range from the 8th to 17th centuries.
[src:americas/africa-p01] A Lunda state formed in the Nkalany Valley (estimates range from c.
[src:americas/africa-p01] 1700), in the 18th century, Lunda rapidly expanded into an extensive commonwealth across the southern savanna, using the institutions of perpetual kinship and positional succession to incorporate peoples.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Meanwhile, Luba expanded its number of tributaries, in some cases using its widely acknowledged prestige to intervene in succession disputes and distribute ritually-powerful royal regalia related to *bulopwe* (sacred kingship), in other cases using conquest.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the northern Great Lakes, the Empire of Kitara rose around the 11th century, famed for its oral traditions.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Peter Robertshaw considered its rulers (the Chwezi) to have been religious leaders who utilised networks of hill-top shrines to project authority.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Around 1500, severe droughts and famine destabilised the region, occurring again during the early-17th and 18th centuries.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Luo-speaking peoples migrated from the Upper Nile basin into modern-day Uganda, and a Biito dynasty replaced the Chwezi in Bunyoro-Kitara.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Over the following centuries, the kingdoms of Bunyoro-Kitara, Buganda, and Rwanda struggled for hegemony among others.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Throughout the 16th and 17th centuries, Bunyoro raided states to the south such as Nkore and Rwanda.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Mpororo rose and fragmented during the 18th century, while Buganda rapidly expanded at the expense of Bunyoro to become the major power in the region.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The East African interior was inhabited by pastoralist Cushitic and Nilotic speakers, along with Bantu speakers who continued to expand and adapt to their lands while absorbing the former two; the 17th century saw the establishment of tributary systems that stabilised the region.
[src:americas/africa-p01] On the Swahili coast the Swahili city-states thrived off of the Indian Ocean trade and gradually Islamized, giving rise to the Kilwa Sultanate from the 10th century.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the 15th century, trade routes for Zimbabwean gold shifted north, weakening Kilwa.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The Portuguese arrived at the coast soon after, and exploited divisions between coastal city-states to gain control over them while utilising a powerful navy.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the 17th and 18th centuries, Lamu-Swahili cities rebelled against the Portuguese and allied the Omani Empire which supplanted Portuguese rule.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Madagascar was settled by Austronesian peoples between the 5th and 7th centuries, as societies organized at the behest of *hasina* and competed over with one another over the island's estuaries and bridgeheads.
[src:americas/africa-p01] From around the 15th century, southern Madagascar became integrated into global trade; the Sakalava Empire rose to dominate west-coastal trade, accompanied by numerous other states, and the island saw several failed European colonial ventures.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In Southern Africa, an early kingdom was Mapungubwe, which collapsed c.
[src:americas/africa-p01] 1300 as Great Zimbabwe, with its monumental dry-stone walls, rose to become the region's main political and economic centre.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Following shifting trade routes north to the Zambezi and unclear circumstances, Great Zimbabwe entered into decline and was succeeded by the Mutapa Empire and Kingdom of Butua in the 15th century.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Mutapa was briefly vassalised by the Portuguese in the 17th century, the latter-half of which saw widespread famine and disease, until Changamire Dombo revolted in the 1680s, conquered Butua to found the Rozvi Empire, and expelled all Portuguese from the Zimbabwean Plateau.
[src:americas/africa-p01] North of the Zambezi, Maravi around Lake Malawi expanded in the 17th century, but the collapse of its succession system in the 18th century precipitated its disintegration.
[src:americas/africa-p01] By the late-1st millennium CE, Bantu-speaking farmers populated most of Southern Africa's cultivable savannas, reaching southwards to the Kei River; they traded goods such as livestock, grain, and metal tools between communities and with hunter-gatherers.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Further south, the Dutch began colonizing the western Cape in the 17th century, and Britain seized control of the colony around the turn of the 19th century.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the late-18th century, the interplay of pre-existing trends of political centralization with the effects of international trade, environmental instability, and European colonisation set the *Mfecane* ("Crushing") in motion, as various African states were founded.
[src:americas/africa-p01] By the turn of the 19th century, many of Africa's economic and political structures were unstable and brittle as a result of long-term effects of the slave trade.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In Egypt Muhammad Ali led a national movement to seize power from Ottoman suzerainty, instituting sweeping reforms and greatly strengthening Egyptian power by militaristic expansion.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Meanwhile, in West Africa the Fula *jihad*s, which had been gaining momentum throughout the 18th century, culminated in the establishment of the expansive Sokoto and Hamdullahi caliphates.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In the Horn, Ethiopia underwent reforms, seeking to revive the imperial state, something that was later achieved by Menelik II's conquests.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In Southern Africa the *Mfecane* propelled large long-distance migrations that caused widespread disruption across the vast region, while several Boer republics were founded.
[src:americas/africa-p01] European campaigns to abolish the Atlantic slave trade led to supply refocusing on internal markets and saw the rapid growth of the Indian Ocean slave trade.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Across the continent many rulers attempted reforms and indigenous forms of 'modernisation', however these efforts were consistently undermined by European traders and missionaries as the tide of European encroachment rose.
[src:americas/africa-p01] For 400 years, European nations had mainly limited their involvement to trading stations on the African coast, with few daring to venture inland.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The Industrial Revolution in Europe produced several technological innovations which assisted them in overcoming this 400-year pattern.
[src:americas/africa-p01] One was the development of repeating rifles, which were easier and quicker to load than muskets.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Maxim developed the maxim gun, the model of the modern-day machine gun.
[src:americas/africa-p01] European states kept these weapons largely among themselves by refusing to sell these weapons to African leaders.
[src:americas/africa-p01] African germs took numerous European lives and deterred permanent settlements.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Diseases such as yellow fever, sleeping sickness, yaws, and leprosy made Africa a very inhospitable place for Europeans.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The deadliest disease was malaria, endemic throughout Tropical Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In 1854, the discovery of quinine and other medical innovations helped to make conquest and colonisation in Africa possible.
[src:americas/africa-p01] There were strong motives for the conquest of Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Raw materials were needed for European factories, and free trade was championed to prevent Africans from regulating their economies.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Prestige and imperial rivalries were at play.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Acquiring African colonies would show rivals that a nation was powerful and significant.
[src:americas/africa-p01] These contextual factors forged the Scramble for Africa; during the late-19th and early-20th centuries the European powers partitioned and conquered almost all of Africa despite fierce resistance (only Ethiopia and Liberia remained independent).
[src:americas/africa-p01] Traditional leaders were incorporated into the colonial regimes as a form of indirect rule to extract human and natural resources and curb organized resistance.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Colonial borders were drawn unilaterally by the Europeans, often cutting across bonds of kinship, language, culture, and established routes, and sometimes incorporating groups who previously had little in common.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The threat to trade routes was mitigated by poor policing and African entrepreneurs (viewed as smugglers) who exploited the differing tax and legal schemes.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The first few decades of European colonialism saw intense violence, disorder, and atrocities, such as that of the Congo Free State, German South West Africa, and French Algeria, with the late colonial period relatively peaceful in comparison.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Colonial rule had wide-reaching effects on African societies, such as the spread of Christianity as part of the 'civilising mission'.
[src:americas/africa-p01] African culture was strongly denigrated and persecuted, as pervasive racial discrimination deepened the scars of humiliation.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Imperial rule by Europeans continued until after the conclusion of World War II, when almost all remaining colonial territories gradually obtained formal independence.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Independence movements in Africa gained momentum following World War II, which left the major European powers weakened.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In 1951, Libya, a former Italian colony, gained independence.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In 1956, Tunisia and Morocco won their independence from France.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Ghana followed suit the next year (March 1957), becoming the first of the sub-Saharan colonies to be granted independence.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Over the next decade, waves of decolonisation took place across the continent, culminating in the 1960 Year of Africa and the establishment of the Organisation of African Unity in 1963.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Portugal's overseas presence in sub-Saharan Africa (most notably in Angola, Cape Verde, Mozambique, Guinea-Bissau, and São Tomé and Príncipe) lasted from the 16th century to 1975, after the Estado Novo regime was overthrown in a military coup in Lisbon.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Rhodesia unilaterally declared independence from the United Kingdom in 1965, under the white minority government of Ian Smith, but was not internationally recognised as an independent state (as Zimbabwe) until 1980, when black nationalists gained power after a bitter guerrilla war.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Although South Africa was one of the first African countries to gain independence, the state remained under the control of the country's white minority, initially through qualified voting rights and from 1956 by a system of racial segregation known as apartheid, until 1994.
[src:americas/africa-p01] As of 2025, Africa contains 54 sovereign countries.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Since independence, African states have frequently been hampered by instability, corruption, violence, and authoritarianism.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The vast majority of African states are republics that operate under some form of the presidential system of rule.
[src:americas/africa-p01] However, few of them have been able to sustain democratic governments on a permanent basis—per the criteria laid out by Lührmann et al.
[src:americas/africa-p01] (2018), only Botswana and Mauritius have been consistently democratic for the entirety of their post-colonial history.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Most African countries have experienced several coups or periods of military dictatorship.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Between 1990 and 2018, though, the continent as a whole has trended towards more democratic governance.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Upon independence an overwhelming majority of Africans lived in extreme poverty.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The continent suffered from the lack of infrastructural or industrial development under colonial rule, along with political instability.
[src:americas/africa-p01] With limited financial resources or access to global markets, relatively stable countries such as Kenya still experienced only very slow economic development.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Only a handful of African countries succeeded in obtaining rapid economic growth prior to 1990.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Exceptions include Libya and Equatorial Guinea, both of which possess large oil reserves.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Instability throughout the continent after decolonisation resulted primarily from marginalisation of ethnic groups, and corruption.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Faced with increasingly frequent and severe violence, military rule was widely accepted by the population of many countries as means to maintain order, and during the 1970s and 1980s a majority of African countries were controlled by military dictatorships.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Territorial disputes between nations and rebellions by groups seeking independence were also common in independent African states.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The most devastating of these was the Nigerian Civil War, fought between government forces and an Igbo separatist republic, which resulted in a famine that killed 1–2 million people.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Two civil wars in Sudan, the first lasting from 1955 to 1972 and the second from 1983 to 2005, collectively killed around 3 million.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Both were fought primarily on ethnic and religious lines.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Cold War conflicts between the United States and the Soviet Union also contributed to instability.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Both the Soviet Union and the United States offered considerable incentives to African political and military leaders who aligned themselves with the superpowers' foreign policy.
[src:americas/africa-p01] As an example, during the Angolan Civil War, the Soviet and Cuban aligned MPLA and the American aligned UNITA received the vast majority of their military and political support from these countries.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Many African countries became highly dependent on foreign aid.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The sudden loss of both Soviet and American aid at the end of the Cold War and fall of the USSR resulted in severe economic and political turmoil in the countries most dependent on foreign support.
[src:americas/africa-p01] There was a major famine in Ethiopia between 1983 and 1985, killing up to 1.2 million people, which most historians attribute primarily to the forced relocation of farmworkers and seizure of grain by the communist Derg government, further exacerbated by the civil war.
[src:americas/africa-p01] In 1994 a genocide in Rwanda resulted in up to 800,000 deaths, added to a severe refugee crisis and fuelled the rise of militia groups in neighbouring countries.
[src:americas/africa-p01] This contributed to the outbreak of the first and second Congo Wars, which were the most devastating military conflicts in modern Africa, with up to 5.5 million deaths, making it by far the deadliest conflict in modern African history and one of the costliest wars in human history.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Various conflicts between various insurgent groups and governments continue.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Since 2003, there has been an ongoing conflict in Darfur (Sudan), which peaked in intensity from 2003 to 2005 with notable spikes in violence in 2007 and 2013–15, killing around 300,000 people total.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The Boko Haram Insurgency primarily within Nigeria (with considerable fighting in Niger, Chad, and Cameroon as well) has killed around 350,000 people since 2009.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Most African conflicts have been reduced to low-intensity conflicts as of 2022.
[src:americas/africa-p01] However, the Tigray War from 2020 to 2022 killed an estimated 300,000–500,000 people, primarily due to famine.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Overall though, violence across Africa has greatly declined in the 21st century, with the end of civil wars in Angola, Sierra Leone, and Algeria in 2002, Liberia in 2003, and Sudan and Burundi in 2005.
[src:americas/africa-p01] The Second Congo War, which involved 9 countries and several insurgent groups, ended in 2003.
[src:americas/africa-p01] This decline in violence coincided with many countries abandoning communist-style command economies and opening up for market reforms, which over the course of the 1990s and 2000s promoted the establishment of permanent, peaceful trade between neighbouring countries (see Capitalist peace).
[src:americas/africa-p01] Improved stability and economic reforms have led to a great increase in foreign investment into many African nations, mainly from China, which further spurred economic growth.
[src:americas/africa-p01] Between 2000 and 2014, annual GDP growth in sub-Saharan Africa averaged 5.02%, doubling its total GDP from $811 billion to $1.63 trillion (constant 2015 USD).
[src:americas/africa-p01] North Africa experienced comparable growth rates.
[src:americas/africa-p01] A significant part of this growth can also be attributed to the facilitated diffusion of information technologies and specifically the mobile telephone.
[src:americas/africa-p01] While several individual countries have maintained high growth rates, since 2014 overall growth has considerably slowed, primarily as a result of falling commodity prices, continued lack of industrialisation, and epidemics such as Ebola and COVID-19.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Africa is the largest of the three great southward projections from the largest landmass of the Earth.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Separated from Europe by the Mediterranean Sea, it is joined to Asia at its northeast extremity by the Isthmus of Suez (transected by the Suez Canal), 163 km (101 mi) wide.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Geopolitically, Egypt's Sinai Peninsula east of the Suez Canal is often considered part of Africa as well.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The coastline is 26,000 km (16,000 mi) long, and the absence of deep indentations of the shore is illustrated by the fact that Europe, which covers only 10,400,000 km2 (4,000,000 sq mi) – about a third of the surface of Africa – has a coastline of 32,000 km (20,000 mi).
[src:americas/africa-p02] From the most northerly point, Ras ben Sakka in Tunisia (37°21' N), to the most southerly point, Cape Agulhas in South Africa (34°51'15" S), is a distance of approximately 8,000 km (5,000 mi).
[src:americas/africa-p02] Cape Verde, 17°33'22" W, the westernmost point, is a distance of approximately 7,400 km (4,600 mi) to Ras Hafun, 51°27'52" E, the most easterly projection that neighbours Cape Guardafui, the tip of the Horn of Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Africa's largest country is Algeria, and its smallest country is Seychelles, an archipelago off the east coast.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The smallest nation on the continental mainland is The Gambia.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The African plate, also known as the Nubian plate, is a major tectonic plate that includes most of the continent of Africa (except for its easternmost part) and the adjacent oceanic crust to the west and south.
[src:americas/africa-p02] It also includes a narrow strip of Western Asia along the Mediterranean Sea, including much of Israel, Palestine and Lebanon.
[src:americas/africa-p02] It is bounded by the North American plate and South American plate to the west (separated by the Mid-Atlantic Ridge); the Arabian plate and Somali plate to the east; the Eurasian plate, Aegean Sea plate and Anatolian plate to the north; and the Antarctic plate to the south.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Between 60 million years ago and 10 million years ago, the Somali plate began rifting from the African plate along the East African Rift.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Since the continent of Africa consists of crust from both the African and the Somali plates, some literature refers to the African plate as the *Nubian plate* to distinguish it from the continent as a whole.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The climate of Africa ranges from tropical to subarctic on its highest peaks.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Its northern half is primarily desert, or arid, while its central and southern areas contain both savanna plains and dense jungle (rainforest) regions.
[src:americas/africa-p02] In between, there is a convergence, where vegetation patterns such as sahel and steppe dominate.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Africa is the hottest continent on Earth and 60% of the entire land surface consists of drylands and deserts.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The record for the highest-ever recorded temperature, in Libya in 1922 (58 °C (136 °F)), was discredited in 2013.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Climate change in Africa is a serious threat because the continent is one of the most vulnerable regions to the effects of climate change, despite being responsible for less than 4% of global greenhouse emissions.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Climate change is causing increasingly erratic rainfall patterns, more frequent extreme weather events such as droughts, floods, and rising sea-surface temperatures across the continent.
[src:americas/africa-p02] These changes threaten food and water security, biodiversity, public health, and economic development.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Africa is currently warming faster than the rest of the world on average.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Climate change intensifies existing socioeconomic vulnerabilities.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Large segments of the African population depend on climate-sensitive livelihoods such as agriculture (55 - 62% of the workforce in sub-Saharan Africa) and already live in poverty, heightening their exposure to shocks.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Health outcomes worsen as heat stress, vector-borne diseases (such as malaria and dengue), and malnutrition become more prevalent.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Over half (56%) of the over 2,000 recorded public health incidents in Africa between 2001 and 2021 were connected to climate change.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Resource scarcity contributes to displacement and conflict, particularly in fragile regions.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Urban areas, often characterized by informal settlements, face heightened risks from flooding and extreme heat.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Africa has over 3,000 protected areas, with 198 marine protected areas, 50 biosphere reserves, and 80 wetlands reserves.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Significant habitat destruction, increases in human population and poaching are reducing Africa's biological diversity and arable land.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Human encroachment, civil unrest and the introduction of non-native species threaten biodiversity in Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p02] This has been exacerbated by administrative problems, inadequate personnel and funding problems.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Deforestation is affecting Africa at twice the world rate, according to the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP).
[src:americas/africa-p02] The deforestation rate of 4.08 million hectares in 2000–2015 declined to 3.45 million ha per year in 2015–2025.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Some sources claim that approximately 90% of the original, virgin forests in West Africa have been destroyed.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Over 90% of Madagascar's original forests have been destroyed since the arrival of humans 2000 years ago.
[src:americas/africa-p02] About 65% of Africa's agricultural land suffers from soil degradation.
[src:americas/africa-p02] It is also home to a variety of "jungle" animals including snakes and primates and aquatic life such as crocodiles and amphibians.
[src:americas/africa-p02] In addition, Africa has the largest number of megafauna species, as it was least affected by the extinction of the Pleistocene megafauna.
[src:americas/africa-p02] African environmental problems are problems caused by the direct and indirect human impacts on the natural environment and affect humans and nearly all forms of life in Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Issues include deforestation, soil degradation, air pollution, water pollution, coastal erosion, garbage pollution, climate change, Oil spills, Biodiversity loss, and water scarcity (resulting in problems with access to safe water supply and sanitation).
[src:americas/africa-p02] These issues result in environmental conflict and are connected to broader social struggles for democracy and sovereignty.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The scarcity of climate adaptation techniques in Africa makes it the least resilient continent to climate change.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The African Union (AU) is a continental union consisting of 55 member states.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The union was formed, with Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, as its headquarters, on 26 June 2001.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The union was officially established on 9 July 2002 as a successor to the Organisation of African Unity (OAU).
[src:americas/africa-p02] In July 2004, the African Union's Pan-African Parliament (PAP) was relocated to Midrand, in South Africa, but the African Commission on Human and Peoples' Rights remained in Addis Ababa.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The African Union, not to be confused with the AU Commission, is formed by the Constitutive Act of the African Union, which aims to transform the African Economic Community, a federated commonwealth, into a state under established international conventions.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The African Union has a parliamentary government, known as the African Union Government, consisting of legislative, judicial and executive organs.
[src:americas/africa-p02] It is led by the African Union President and Head of State, who is also the President of the Pan-African Parliament.
[src:americas/africa-p02] A person becomes AU President by being elected to the PAP, and subsequently gaining majority support in the PAP.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The government of the AU consists of all-union, regional, state, and municipal authorities, as well as hundreds of institutions, that together manage the day-to-day affairs of the institution.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Extensive human rights abuses still occur in several parts of Africa, often under the oversight of the state.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Most of such violations occur for political reasons, often as a side effect of civil war.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Countries where major human rights violations have been reported in recent times include the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Sierra Leone, Liberia, Sudan, Zimbabwe, and Ivory Coast.
[src:americas/africa-p02] African nations have made great efforts to respect international borders as inviolate for a long time.
[src:americas/africa-p02] For example, the Organization of African Unity (OAU), which was established in 1963 and replaced by the African Union in 2002, set the respect for the territorial integrity of each country as one of its principles in OAU Charter.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Indeed, compared with the formation of European countries, there have been fewer international conflicts in Africa for changing the borders, which has influenced country formation there and has enabled some countries to survive that might have been defeated and absorbed by others.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Yet international conflicts have played out by support for proxy armies or rebel movements.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Many states have experienced civil wars: including Rwanda, Sudan, Angola, Sierra Leone, Congo, Liberia, Ethiopia and Somalia.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Wars of national liberation also often took up a Marxist, Marxist–Leninist, or Maoist character in ideological terms, where the independence of African nations was raised in Marxian terms.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Early examples included the Union of the Peoples of Cameroon armed movement against French colonialism, a Marxist–Leninist insurgency, followed by similar movements in Congo (the Simba Rebellion).
[src:americas/africa-p02] Che Guevara participated in the latter, and opined in 1967 that Africa was not ready for revolution.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Despite this, in Zanzibar before and after unification with Tanzania, forms of socialism took hold.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Even after 1990, there are some examples of Military Marxism, such as a militia established by Ernest Wamba-dia-Wamba in Eastern Congo in the 1990s.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The countries in this table are categorised according to the scheme for geographic subregions used by the United Nations, and data included are per sources in cross-referenced articles.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Where they differ, provisos are clearly indicated.
[src:americas/africa-p02] This list contains nine territories that are administered as incorporated areas of a primarily non-African country but that belong geographically to the African continent.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The continent's total nominal GDP remains behind that of several individual countries, including the United States, China, Japan, Germany, the United Kingdom, India and France.
[src:americas/africa-p02] According to the United Nations' Human Development Report in 2003, the bottom 24 ranked nations (151st to 175th) were all African.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Poverty, illiteracy, malnutrition, inadequate water supply and sanitation, and poor health affect a large proportion of the people who reside on the African continent.
[src:americas/africa-p02] In August 2008, the World Bank announced revised global poverty estimates based on a new international poverty line of $1.25 per day (versus the previous measure of $1.00).
[src:americas/africa-p02] Eighty-one percent of the sub-Saharan African population was living on less than $2.50 (PPP) per day in 2005, compared with 86% for India.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Sub-Saharan Africa is the least successful region of the world in reducing poverty ($1.25 per day); some 50% of the population living in poverty in 1981 (200 million people), a figure that rose to 58% in 1996 before dropping to 50% in 2005 (380 million people).
[src:americas/africa-p02] The average poor person in sub-Saharan Africa is estimated to live on only 70 cents per day, and was poorer in 2003 than in 1973, indicating increasing poverty in some areas.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Some of it is attributed to unsuccessful economic liberalisation programmes spearheaded by foreign companies and governments, but other studies have cited bad domestic government policies more than external factors.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Africa is now at risk of being in debt once again, particularly in sub-Saharan African countries.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The last debt crisis in 2005 was resolved with help from the heavily indebted poor countries scheme (HIPC).
[src:americas/africa-p02] The HIPC resulted in some positive and negative effects on the economy in Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p02] About ten years after the 2005 debt crisis in sub-Saharan Africa was resolved, Zambia fell back into debt.
[src:americas/africa-p02] A small reason was due to the fall in copper prices in 2011, but the bigger reason was that a large amount of the money Zambia borrowed was wasted or pocketed by the elite.
[src:americas/africa-p02] From 1995 to 2005, Africa's rate of economic growth increased, averaging 5% in 2005.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Some countries experienced still higher growth rates, notably Angola, Sudan and Equatorial Guinea, all of which had recently begun extracting their petroleum reserves or had expanded their oil extraction capacity.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The following table shows the projected nominal GDP and GDP per capita (at purchasing power parity) in 2026 by the IMF.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The continent is believed to hold 90% of the world's cobalt, 90% of its platinum, 50% of its gold, 98% of its chromium, 70% of its tantalite, 64% of its manganese and one-third of its uranium.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) has 70% of the world's coltan, a mineral used in the production of tantalum capacitors for electronic devices such as cell phones.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The DRC also has more than 30% of the world's diamond reserves.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Guinea is the world's largest exporter of bauxite.
[src:americas/africa-p02] As the growth in Africa has been driven mainly by services and not manufacturing or agriculture, it has been growth without jobs and without reduction in poverty levels.
[src:americas/africa-p02] In fact, the food security crisis of 2008, which took place following the global financial crisis, pushed 100 million people into food insecurity.
[src:americas/africa-p02] In 2024 nearly 307 million people in Africa were undernourished (46% of the global total), an increase of 10 million people since 2023 and 34 million from 2022.
[src:americas/africa-p02] In recent years, China has built increasingly stronger ties with African nations and is Africa's largest trading partner.
[src:americas/africa-p02] In 2007, Chinese companies invested a total of US$1 billion in Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p02] A Harvard University study led by professor Calestous Juma showed that Africa could feed itself by making the transition from importer to self-sufficiency.
[src:americas/africa-p02] "African agriculture is at the crossroads; we have come to the end of a century of policies that favoured Africa's export of raw materials and importation of food.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Cooking with biogas in Tanzania; Geothermal energy infrastructure in Kenya; Coal power station in South Africa; Solar-powered lamp-light in Zambia.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Energy in Africa is characterised by low per-capita consumption and limited access to modern energy services, reflecting both infrastructural and socio-economic challenges across the continent.
[src:americas/africa-p02] As of 2023, Africa accounted for just 5.5% of global total final energy consumption, with per-capita energy use more than three times lower than the global average.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The energy mix is dominated by biofuels and waste, which make up 43% of total final consumption, primarily for household cooking and heating, followed by oil products at 33%, electricity at 11%, natural gas at 9%, and coal at 4%.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Electricity access remains a major challenge, particularly in Sub-Saharan Africa, where nearly 450 million rural residents lack reliable electricity, and grid coverage is often inconsistent.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Clean cooking solutions are similarly underdeveloped, leaving over 900 million people reliant on polluting fuels such as firewood, charcoal, and agricultural residues, which disproportionately affect women and children.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Transport energy is dominated by oil products, reflecting low motorisation rates and limited adoption of electric mobility, although countries such as Ethiopia, Morocco, and Egypt have begun adopting policies to reduce fossil fuel dependency.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Africa possesses some of the world's most abundant energy resources, including oil, natural gas, coal, hydropower, solar, wind, geothermal, and biomass, much of which remains underutilised.
[src:americas/africa-p02] While fossil fuels such as coal, oil, and natural gas continue to dominate energy production and electricity generation in Africa, renewable sources are increasingly expanding across the continent.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Hydropower, solar, wind, geothermal, and modern biomass are growing in capacity, though their deployment remains uneven and limited compared to the continent's vast potential.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Hydropower is the largest non-combustible renewable source, while solar energy offers immense potential due to high irradiation levels, particularly in the Sahara and Sahel.
[src:americas/africa-p02] There are regional differences: North Africa is dominated by oil and gas production, Southern Africa by coal and hydropower, East Africa by hydropower and geothermal, and West and Central Africa face major electrification gaps despite hydroelectric potential.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Water development and management are complex in Africa due to the multiplicity of trans-boundary water resources (rivers, lakes and aquifers).
[src:americas/africa-p02] Around 75% of sub-Saharan Africa falls within 53 international river basin catchments that traverse multiple borders.
[src:americas/africa-p02] This particular constraint can also be converted into an opportunity if the potential for trans-boundary cooperation is harnessed in the development of the area's water resources.
[src:americas/africa-p02] A multi-sectoral analysis of the Zambezi River, for example, shows that riparian cooperation could lead to a 23% increase in firm energy production without any additional investments.
[src:americas/africa-p02] A number of institutional and legal frameworks for transboundary cooperation exist, such as the Zambezi River Authority, the Southern African Development Community (SADC) Protocol, Volta River Authority and the Nile Basin Commission.
[src:americas/africa-p02] However, additional efforts are required to further develop political will, as well as the financial capacities and institutional frameworks needed for win-win multilateral cooperative actions and optimal solutions for all riparians.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Africa is considered by anthropologists to be the most genetically diverse continent as a result of being the longest inhabited.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Africa's population has rapidly increased over the last 40 years, and is consequently relatively young.
[src:americas/africa-p02] In some African states, more than half the population is under 25 years of age.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The total number of people in Africa increased from 229 million in 1950 to 630 million in 1990.
[src:americas/africa-p02] As of 2021, the population of Africa is estimated at 1,394 million.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Africa's total population surpassing other continents is fairly recent; African population surpassed Europe in the 1990s, while the Americas was overtaken sometime around the year 2000.
[src:americas/africa-p02] This increase in number of babies born in Africa compared to the rest of the world is expected to reach approximately 37% in the year 2050; while in 1990 sub-Saharan Africa accounted for only 16% of the world's births.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The total fertility rate (children per woman) for Sub-Saharan Africa is 4.7 as of 2018, the highest in the world.
[src:americas/africa-p02] All countries in sub-Saharan Africa had TFRs (average number of children) above replacement level in 2019 and accounted for 27.1% of global livebirths.
[src:americas/africa-p02] In 2021, sub-Saharan Africa accounted for 29% of global births.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Speakers of Bantu languages (part of the Niger–Congo family) are the majority in southern, central and southeast Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The Bantu-speaking peoples from the Sahel progressively expanded over most of sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p02] But there are also several Nilotic groups in South Sudan and East Africa, the mixed Swahili people on the Swahili Coast, and a few remaining indigenous Khoisan ("San" or "Bushmen") and Pygmy peoples in Southern and Central Africa, respectively.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Bantu-speaking Africans also predominate in Gabon and Equatorial Guinea, and are found in parts of southern Cameroon.
[src:americas/africa-p02] In the Kalahari Desert of Southern Africa, the distinct people known as the Bushmen (also "San", closely related to, but distinct from "Hottentots") have long been present.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The San are physically distinct from other Africans and are the indigenous people of southern Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Pygmies are the pre-Bantu indigenous peoples of central Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The peoples of West Africa primarily speak Niger–Congo languages, belonging mostly to its non-Bantu branches, though some Nilo-Saharan and Afro-Asiatic speaking groups are also found.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The Niger–Congo-speaking Yoruba, Igbo, Fulani, Akan, and Wolof ethnic groups are the largest and most influential.
[src:americas/africa-p02] In the central Sahara, Mandinka or Mande groups are most significant.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Chadic-speaking groups, including the Hausa, are found in more northerly parts of the region nearest to the Sahara, and Nilo-Saharan communities, such as the Songhai, Kanuri, and Zarma, are found in the eastern parts of West Africa bordering Central Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The peoples of North Africa consist of three main indigenous groups: Berbers in the northwest, Egyptians in the northeast, and Nilo-Saharan-speaking peoples in the east.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The Arabs who arrived in the 7th century AD introduced the Arabic language and Islam to North Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The Semitic Phoenicians (who founded Carthage) and Hyksos, the Indo-Iranian Alans, the Indo-European Greeks, Romans, and Vandals settled in North Africa as well.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Significant Berber communities remain within Morocco and Algeria in the 21st century, while, to a lesser extent, Berber speakers are also present in some regions of Tunisia and Libya.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The Berber-speaking Tuareg and other often-nomadic peoples are the principal inhabitants of the Saharan interior of North Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p02] In Mauritania, there is a small but near-extinct Berber community in the north and Niger–Congo-speaking peoples in the south, though in both regions Arabic and Arab culture predominates.
[src:americas/africa-p02] In Sudan, although Arabic and Arab culture predominate, it is mostly inhabited by groups that originally spoke Nilo-Saharan, such as the Nubians, Fur, Masalit and Zaghawa, who, over the centuries, have variously intermixed with migrants from the Arabian peninsula.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Small communities of Afro-Asiatic-speaking Beja nomads can also be found in Egypt and Sudan.
[src:americas/africa-p02] In the Horn of Africa, some Ethiopian and Eritrean groups (like the Amhara and Tigrayans, collectively known as Habesha) speak languages from the Semitic branch of the Afro-Asiatic language family, while the Oromo and Somali speak languages from the Cushitic branch of Afro-Asiatic.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Prior to the decolonisation movements of the post-World War II era, Europeans were represented in every part of Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Decolonization during the 1960s and 1970s often resulted in the mass emigration of white settlers—especially from Algeria and Morocco (1.6 million *pieds-noirs* in North Africa), Kenya, Congo, Rhodesia, Mozambique and Angola.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Between 1975 and 1977, over a million colonials returned to Portugal alone.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Nevertheless, white Africans remain an important minority in many African states, particularly Zimbabwe, Namibia, Réunion, and South Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The country with the largest white African population is South Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Dutch and British diasporas represent the largest communities of European ancestry on the continent today.
[src:americas/africa-p02] European colonisation also brought sizable groups of Asians, particularly from the Indian subcontinent, to British colonies.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Large Indian communities are found in South Africa, and smaller ones are present in Kenya, Tanzania, and some other southern and southeast African countries.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The large Indian community in Uganda was expelled by the dictator Idi Amin in 1972, though many have since returned.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The islands in the Indian Ocean are also populated primarily by people of Asian origin, often mixed with Africans and Europeans.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The Malagasy people of Madagascar are an Austronesian people, but those along the coast are generally mixed with Bantu, Arab, Indian and European origins.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Malay and Indian ancestries are also important components in the group of people known in South Africa as Cape Coloureds (people with origins in two or more races and continents).
[src:americas/africa-p02] During the 20th century, small but economically important communities of Lebanese have also developed in the larger coastal cities of West and East Africa, respectively.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The Sahara served as a trans-regional passageway and place of dwelling for people in Africa during various humid phases and periods throughout the history of Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p02] As early as 11,000 years ago, Sub-Saharan West Africans, bearing macrohaplogroup L (e.g., L1b1a11, L1b1a6a, L1b1a8, L1b1a9a1, L2a1k, L3d1b1a), may have migrated through North Africa and into Europe, mostly into southern Europe (e.g., Iberia).
[src:americas/africa-p02] The genetic marker E1b1 was identified to have wide distribution across Egypt, with "P2/215/M35.1 (E1b1b), for short M35, likely also originated in eastern tropical Africa, and is predominantly distributed in an arc from the Horn of Africa up through Egypt".
[src:americas/africa-p02] The R haplogroup has also been identified to have high frequencies in central Saharan Africa, among some Afro-Asiatic and Nilo-Saharan language speaking groups.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Genetic evidence has identified the Horn of Africa to be the source of a genetic marker "M35/215" Y-chromosome lineage for a significant population component which moved north from that region into Egypt and the Levant.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Historian Christopher Ehret argued that this genetic distribution paralleled the spread of the Afrasian language family with the movement of people from the Horn of Africa into Egypt and added a new demic component to the existing population of Egypt 17,000 years ago.
[src:americas/africa-p02] According to a recent study, the Arab migrations to the Maghreb was mainly a demographic process that heavily implied gene flow and remodelled the genetic structure of the Maghreb region in North Africa, rather than a mere cultural replacement as claimed by older studies.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Another study found out that the majority of J-M267 (Eu10) chromosomes in the Maghreb are due to the recent gene flow caused by the Arab migrations to the Maghreb in the first millennium CE as both southern Qahtanite and northern Adnanite Arabs added to the heterogenous Maghrebi ethnic melting pot.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The Eu10 chromosome pool in the Maghreb is derived not only from early Neolithic dispersions from Western Asia but to a much greater extent from recent expansions of Arab tribes from the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:americas/africa-p02] David Schoenbrun, Christopher Ehret, Steven A.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Brandt and Shomarka Keita (2025) have highlighted the problematic categorisation of genetic haplogroups characterised as ‘African’ and ‘Eurasian' in North African genome studies.
[src:americas/africa-p02] In reference to the van de Loosdrecht et al.
[src:americas/africa-p02] In their view, identifying a range of African populations may still remain an issue “since the idea of ‘African’ still gets stereotyped or restricted.
[src:americas/africa-p02] (Accepting the southwestern Asian/Levantine geographical continuity with Africa eliminates a conceptual barrier related to racio-typological thinking permitting an Africasian construct analogous to Eurasian.)”.
[src:americas/africa-p02] While Africans profess a wide variety of religious beliefs, the majority of the people respect African religions or parts of them.
[src:americas/africa-p02] However, in formal surveys or census, most people will identify with major religions that came from outside the continent, mainly through colonisation.
[src:americas/africa-p02] There are several reasons for this, the main one being the colonial idea that African religious beliefs and practices are not good enough.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Religious beliefs and statistics on religious affiliation are difficult to come by since they are often a sensitive topic for governments with mixed religious populations.
[src:americas/africa-p02] According to the *World Book Encyclopedia*, Islam and Christianity are the two largest religions in Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Islam is most prevalent in Northern Africa, and is the state religion of many North African countries, such as Algeria, where 99% of the population practices Islam.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The majority of people in most governments in Southern, Southeast, and Central Africa, as well as in a sizable portion of the Horn of Africa and West Africa, identify as Christians.
[src:americas/africa-p02] The Coptic Christians constitute a sizable minority in Egypt, and the Ethiopian Orthodox Church is the largest church in Ethiopia, with 36 million and 51 million adherents.
[src:americas/africa-p02] According to Encyclopædia Britannica, 45% of the population are Christians, 40% are Muslims, and 10% follow traditional religions.
[src:americas/africa-p02] A small number of Africans are Hindu, Buddhist, Confucianist, Baháʼí, or Jewish.
[src:americas/africa-p02] There is also a minority of people in Africa who are irreligious.
[src:americas/africa-p02] By most estimates, well over a thousand languages (UNESCO has estimated around two thousand) are spoken in Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Most are of African origin, though some are of European or Asian origin.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Africa is the most multilingual continent in the world, and it is not rare for individuals to fluently speak not only multiple African languages, but one or more European ones as well.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Following the end of colonialism, nearly all African countries adopted official languages that originated outside the continent, although several countries also granted legal recognition to indigenous languages (such as Swahili, Yoruba, Igbo and Hausa).
[src:americas/africa-p02] In numerous countries, English and French (*see African French*) are used for communication in the public sphere such as government, commerce, education and the media.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Arabic, Portuguese, Afrikaans and Spanish are examples of languages that trace their origin to outside of Africa, and that are used by millions of Africans today, both in the public and private spheres.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Italian is spoken by some in former Italian colonies in Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p02] German is spoken in Namibia, as it was a former German protectorate.
[src:americas/africa-p02] In total, at least a fifth of Africans speak the former colonial languages.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Moreover, in recent years some African countries have been considering removing their official former colonial languages, such as Mali, Burkina Faso and Niger which removed French as an official language in the 2020s in favour of native languages, while also renaming colonial street names.
[src:americas/africa-p02] More than 85% of individuals in Africa use traditional medicine as an alternative to often expensive allopathic medical health care and costly pharmaceutical products.
[src:americas/africa-p02] AIDS in post-colonial Africa is a prevalent issue.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Although the continent is home to about 15.2 percent of the world's population, more than two-thirds of the total infected worldwide—some 35 million people—were Africans, of whom 15 million have already died.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Sub-Saharan Africa alone accounted for an estimated 69 percent of all people living with HIV and 70 percent of all AIDS deaths in 2011.
[src:americas/africa-p02] In the countries of sub-Saharan Africa most affected, AIDS has raised death rates and lowered life expectancy among adults between the ages of 20 and 49 by about twenty years.
[src:americas/africa-p02] Furthermore, the life expectancy in many parts of Africa has declined, largely as a result of the HIV/AIDS epidemic with life-expectancy in some countries reaching as low as thirty-four years.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Africa is divided into a great number of ethnic cultures.
[src:americas/africa-p03] In recent times, the call for a much greater emphasis on the cultural dimension in all aspects of development has become increasingly vocal.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Some aspects of traditional African cultures have become less practised in recent years as a result of neglect and suppression by colonial and post-colonial regimes.
[src:americas/africa-p03] For example, African customs were discouraged, and African languages were prohibited in mission schools, while colonialists such as Leopold II of Belgium attempted to "civilize" Africans by discouraging polygamy and witchcraft.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Abiola Irele and Simon Gikandi comment that the current identity of African literature had its genesis in the "traumatic encounter between Africa and Europe".
[src:americas/africa-p03] On the other hand, Mhoze Chikowero believes that Africans deployed music, dance, spirituality, and other performative cultures to (re)assert themselves as active agents and indigenous intellectuals, to unmake their colonial marginalisation and reshape their own destinies.
[src:americas/africa-p03] As of March 2023, 98 African properties are listed by UNESCO as World Heritage Sites.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Among these proprieties, 54 are cultural sites, 39 are natural sites and 5 are mixed sites.
[src:americas/africa-p03] The List of World Heritage in Danger includes 15 African sites.
[src:americas/africa-p03] African art refers to works of visual art, including works of sculpture, painting, metalwork, and pottery, originating from the various peoples of the African continent and influenced by distinct, indigenous traditions of aesthetic expression.
[src:americas/africa-p03] While the various artistic traditions of such a large and diverse continent display considerable regional and cultural variety, there are consistent artistic themes, recurring motifs, and unifying elements across the broad spectrum of the African visual expression.
[src:americas/africa-p03] As is the case for every artistic tradition in human history, African art was created within specific social, political, and religious contexts.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Likewise, African art was often created not purely for art's sake, but rather with some practical, spiritual, and/or didactic purpose in mind.
[src:americas/africa-p03] In general, African art prioritizes conceptual and symbolic representation over realism, aiming to visualize the subject's spiritual essence.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Ethiopian art, heavily influenced by Ethiopia's long-standing Christian tradition, is also different from most African art, where Traditional African religion (with Islam prevalent in the north east and north west presently) was dominant until the 20th century.
[src:americas/africa-p03] African art includes prehistoric and ancient art, the Islamic art of West Africa, the Christian art of East Africa, and the traditional artifacts of these and other regions.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Many African sculptures were historically made of wood and other natural materials that have not survived from earlier than a few centuries ago, although rare older pottery and metal figures can be found in some areas.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Some of the earliest decorative objects, such as shell beads and evidence of paint, have been discovered in Africa, dating to the Middle Stone Age.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Masks are important elements in the art of many people, along with human figures, and are often highly stylized.
[src:americas/africa-p03] There exist diverse styles, which can often be observed within a single context of origin and may be influenced by the intended use of the object.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Nevertheless, broad regional trends are discernible.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Sculpture is most common among "groups of settled cultivators in the areas drained by the Niger and Congo rivers" in West Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Direct images of deities are relatively infrequent, but masks in particular are or were often made for ritual ceremonies.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Since the late 19th century, there has been an increasing amount of African art in Western collections, the finest pieces of which are displayed as part of the history of colonization.
[src:americas/africa-p03] African art had an important influence on European Modernist art, which was inspired by their interest in abstract depiction.
[src:americas/africa-p03] It was this appreciation of African sculpture that has been attributed to the very concept of "African art", as seen by European and American artists and art historians.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Obidoh Freeborn posits that colonialism is one element that has created the character of modern African art.
[src:americas/africa-p03] According to authors Douglas Fraser and Herbert M.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Author Chika Okeke-Agulu states that "the racist infrastructure of British imperial enterprise forced upon the political and cultural guardians of empire a denial and suppression of an emergent sovereign Africa and modernist art".
[src:americas/africa-p03] scaling: small parts of the structure tend to look similar to larger parts, such as a circular village made of circular houses.
[src:americas/africa-p03] African architecture in some areas has been influenced by external cultures for centuries, according to available evidence.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Western architecture has influenced coastal areas since the late 15th century and is now an important source of inspiration for many larger buildings, particularly in major cities.
[src:americas/africa-p03] African architecture uses a wide range of materials, including thatch, stick/wood, mud, mudbrick, rammed earth, and stone.
[src:americas/africa-p03] These material preferences vary by region: North Africa for stone and rammed earth, the Horn of Africa for stone and mortar, West Africa for mud/adobe, Central Africa for thatch/wood and more perishable materials, Southeast and Southern Africa for stone and thatch/wood.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Cinema of Africa refers to the film industries and films produced in the continent of Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p03] It covers both the history and present of the making or screening of films on the African continent, and also refers to the persons involved in this form of audiovisual culture.
[src:americas/africa-p03] It dates back to the late 19th century, when film reels were the primary cinematic technology in use.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Cairo has been the capital of film industry in Africa since the early 20th century to the present day.
[src:americas/africa-p03] As there are more than 50 countries with audiovisual traditions, there is no one single 'African cinema'.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Both historically and culturally, there are major regional differences between North African and sub-Saharan cinemas, and between the cinemas of different countries.
[src:americas/africa-p03] The Egyptian film industry and the Tunisian are also among the oldest in the world.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Cinema of Egypt in particular is the most established and flourishing industry in Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Pioneers Auguste and Louis Lumière screened their films in Alexandria, Cairo, Tunis, Susa, Libya and Hammam-Lif, Tunisia in 1896.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Albert Samama Chikly is often cited as the first producer of indigenous African cinema, screening his own short documentaries in the casino of Tunis as early as December 1905.
[src:americas/africa-p03] The continent of Africa and its music is vast and highly diverse, with different regions and nations maintaining distinct musical traditions.
[src:americas/africa-p03] African music includes genres such as makwaya, highlife, mbube, township music, jùjú, fuji, jaiva, afrobeat, afrofusion, mbalax, Congolese rumba, soukous, ndombolo, makossa, kizomba, and taarab, among others.
[src:americas/africa-p03] African music also uses a wide variety of instruments from across the continent.
[src:americas/africa-p03] The music and dance traditions of the African diaspora, shaped to varying degrees by African musical traditions, include American genres such as Dixieland jazz, blues, and jazz, as well as Caribbean styles such as calypso (see kaiso), and soca.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Latin American music genres including cumbia, salsa, son cubano, rumba, conga, bomba, samba, and zouk developed from the music of enslaved Africans and have, in turn, influenced contemporary African popular music.
[src:americas/africa-p03] African dance (also Afro dance, Afrodance and Afro-dance) refers to the various dance styles of sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:americas/africa-p03] These dances are closely connected with the traditional rhythms and music traditions of the region.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Music and dancing is an integral part of many traditional African societies.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Songs and dances facilitate teaching and promoting social values, the celebration of special events and major life milestones, the performance of oral history and other recitations, and spiritual experiences.
[src:americas/africa-p03] African dance uses the concepts of polyrhythm and total body articulation.
[src:americas/africa-p03] African dances are often a collective activity performed in large groups, with significant interaction between dancers and onlookers.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Fifty-four African countries have football teams in the Confederation of African Football.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Egypt has won the African Cup seven times, and a record-making three times in a row.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Cameroon, Nigeria, Morocco, Senegal, Ghana, and Algeria have advanced to the knockout stage of recent FIFA World Cups.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Morocco, at the 2022 World Cup in Qatar was the first African nation to reach the semi-finals of the FIFA Men's World Cup.
[src:americas/africa-p03] South Africa hosted the 2010 World Cup tournament, becoming the first African country to do so.
[src:americas/africa-p03] The top clubs in each African football league play the CAF Champions League, while lower-ranked clubs compete in CAF Confederation Cup.
[src:americas/africa-p03] In recent years, the continent has progressed in terms of state-of-the-art basketball facilities, which have been built in cities such as Cairo, Dakar, Johannesburg, Kigali, Luanda, and Rades.
[src:americas/africa-p03] The number of African basketball players who drafted into the U.S.
[src:americas/africa-p03] NBA has experienced growth in the 2010s.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Cricket is popular in some African nations.
[src:americas/africa-p03] South Africa and Zimbabwe have Test status, while Kenya is the leading non-test team and previously had One-Day International cricket (ODI) status (from 10 October 1997, until 30 January 2014).
[src:americas/africa-p03] The three countries jointly hosted the 2003 Cricket World Cup.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Namibia is the other African country to have played in a World Cup.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Morocco, in northern Africa, hosted the 2002 Morocco Cup, but the national team has never qualified for a major tournament.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Rugby is popular in several southern African nations.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Namibia and Zimbabwe have appeared on multiple occasions at the Rugby World Cup, while South Africa is the most successful national team at the Rugby World Cup, having won the tournament on four occasions, in 1995, 2007, 2019, and 2023.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Traditional sports were strictly marginalised during the colonial era, and many are dying or have gone extinct under the pressure of modernisation, however lots remain popular despite not having formal governmental recognition or support.
[src:americas/africa-p03] Some examples are Senegalese wrestling, Dambe, Nguni stick-fighting, and Savika.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] The **African Great Lakes** (Swahili: *Maziwa Makuu*; Kinyarwanda: *Ibiyaga bigari*) are a series of lakes constituting the part of the Rift Valley lakes in and around the East African Rift.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] Collectively, they contain 31,000 km3 (7,400 mi3) of water, which is more than either Lake Baikal or the North American Great Lakes.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] This total constitutes about 25% of the planet's unfrozen surface fresh water.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] The large rift lakes of Africa are the ancient home of great biodiversity, and 10% of the world's fish species live in this region.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] Countries in the area which are bounded by the lakes of the Great Lakes region include Burundi, the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Ethiopia, Kenya, Malawi, Mozambique, Rwanda, Tanzania, Uganda and Zambia.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] The following are included on most lists of the African Great Lakes, grouped by drainage basin.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] The exact number of lakes considered part of the African Great Lakes varies by list, and may include smaller lakes in the rift valleys, especially if they are part of the same drainage basin as the larger lakes, such as Lake Kyoga.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] The Great Lakes region (rarely: *Greater* Lakes region) consists of ten riparian countries: Burundi, the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Ethiopia, Kenya, Malawi, Mozambique, Rwanda, Tanzania, Uganda, and Zambia.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] The adjective *interlacustrine* ("between lakes") can refer to the region, or more specifically, the nations or area bounded by the lakes.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] The Swahili language is the most commonly spoken language in the African Great Lakes region.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] It also serves as a national or official language of five nations in the region: Tanzania, Kenya, Uganda, Rwanda, and the Democratic Republic of the Congo.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] Because of its high population—estimated to be more than 50 million people in 2020—and the agricultural surplus in the region, the area became organized into a number of small states.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] The most powerful of these monarchies were Buganda, Bunyoro, Karagwe, Rwanda, and Burundi.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] Being the long-sought source of the Nile and the watershed triple point between the rivers Nile, Congo and Zambezi, the region had long been of interest to Europeans.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] The first Europeans to arrive in the region in any numbers were Christian missionaries who had limited success in converting the locals, but did open the region to later colonization.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] Increased contact with the rest of the world led to a series of devastating epidemics affecting both humans and livestock.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] While seen as a region with great potential after independence, the Great Lakes region has suffered from civil war and conflict in the four decades around the turn of the 21st century (c.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] In 2022, the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees commended Tanzania for consistently welcoming and aiding refugees from other countries in the region.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] The highlands are relatively cool, with average temperatures ranging between 17 °C (63 °F) and 19 °C (66 °F) and abundant rainfall.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] Major drainage basins include those of the Congo-Zaire, Nile, and Zambezi rivers, which drain into the Atlantic Ocean, Mediterranean Sea, and Indian Ocean, respectively.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] Forests are dominant in the lowlands of the Congo-Zaire Basin, while grasslands and savannas (dry grasslands) are most common in the southern and eastern highlands.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] Temperatures in the lowlands average about 35 °C (95 °F).
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] Around Lake Turkana, the climate is hot and very dry.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] A short rainy season in October is followed by a longer one from April to May.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] The Western Rift Valley lakes are freshwater and home to an extraordinary number of endemic species.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] More than 1,500 cichlid fish species live in the lakes, as well as other fish families.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] The lakes are also important habitats for a number of amphibian species.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] Mammals include elephants, gorillas and hippopotamus.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] The Lake Turkana area is home to hundreds of species of birds endemic to Kenya.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] The East African rift system also serves as a flyway for migrating birds, bringing in hundreds more.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] The birds are essentially supported by plankton masses in the lake, which also feed the fish there.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] Vegetation ranges from rainforest to savanna grasses.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] In some lakes, rapidly growing invasive plants, like the surface-choking water hyacinth and shore-clogging papyrus, are problems.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] Water hyacinth have thus far affected only Lake Victoria.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] Until 12 million years ago, the bountiful waters of the equatorial plateau either flowed west into the Congo River system or east to the Indian Ocean.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] This was changed by the formation of the Great Rift Valley.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] A rift is a weak place in Earth's crust due to the separation of two tectonic plates, often accompanied by a graben, or trough, in which lake water can collect.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] This rift began when East Africa, impelled by currents in the mantle, began separating from the rest of Africa, moving to the northeast.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] The basins that resulted from the geological uplifts filled with water that now flowed north.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] Lake Victoria is not actually within the Rift Valley.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] It occupies a depression between the Eastern and Western Rifts, formed by the uplift of the rifts to either of its sides.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] Around two to three million years ago, Lake Turkana was larger and the area more fertile, making it a center for early hominids.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] Richard Leakey led numerous anthropological excavations in the area, which yielded many important discoveries of hominin remains.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] The two-million-year-old Skull 1470 was found in 1972.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] It was originally thought to be *Homo habilis*, but some anthropologists have assigned it to a new species, *Homo rudolfensis*, named after the lake (previously known as Lake Rudolf).
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] In 1984, the Turkana Boy, a nearly complete skeleton of a *Homo erectus* boy was discovered.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] In 1999, a 3,500,000-year-old skull was discovered there, named *Kenyanthropus platyops*, which means "flat-faced man of Kenya".
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] Fishing—primarily of tilapia species but also of Nile perch—provides the main livelihood for people in the region.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] With four Great Lakes on its borders, Uganda ranks as one of the world's largest producers of freshwater fish.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] The climate and rich volcanic soils in the highlands also sustain intensely cultivated croplands.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] The economies of the Great Lakes region states have different structures and are at various stages of development.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] The GDP real growth rate ranges from 1.8 percent in Burundi to 4.4 in the DRC.
[src:americas/african-great-lakes] GDP per capita fluctuates between $600 in DRC and Burundi and $800 in Uganda.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The **Americas**, sometimes collectively called **America**, are a landmass comprising the totality of North America and South America.
[src:americas/americas-p01] When viewed as a single continent, the Americas are the second largest continent by area after Asia and the third largest continent by population.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The Americas make up most of the land in Earth's Western Hemisphere and constitute the "New World", in contrast to the "Old World" of Afro-Eurasia.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Along with their associated islands, the Americas cover 8% of Earth's total surface area and 28.4% of its land area.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The topography is dominated by the American Cordillera, a long chain of mountains that runs the length of the west coast.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The flatter eastern side of the Americas is dominated by large river basins, such as the Amazon, St.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Lawrence River–Great Lakes, Mississippi, and La Plata basins.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Since the Americas extend 14,000 km (8,700 mi) from north to south, the climate and ecology vary widely, from the arctic tundra of Northern Canada, Greenland, and Alaska, to the tropical rainforests in Central America and South America.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Humans first settled the Americas from Asia between 20,000 and 16,000 years ago.
[src:americas/americas-p01] A second migration of Na-Dene speakers followed later from Asia.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The subsequent migration of the Inuit into the neoarctic c.
[src:americas/americas-p01] 3500 BCE completed what is generally regarded as the settlement by the Indigenous peoples of the Americas.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The Norse colonization of North America saw several settlements established in Greenland, and perhaps on the mainland, however, these were later abandoned.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The Spanish presence involved the enslavement of large numbers of the indigenous population of the Americas.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Diseases introduced from Europe and West Africa devastated the indigenous peoples, and the European powers colonized the Americas.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Mass emigration from Europe, including large numbers of indentured servants, and importation of African slaves largely replaced the indigenous peoples in much of the Americas.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Decolonization of the Americas began with the American Revolution in the 1770s and largely ended with the Spanish–American War in the late 1890s.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The Americas are home to more than a billion inhabitants, two-thirds of whom reside in the United States, Brazil, and Mexico.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The name "America" was first recorded in 1507.
[src:americas/americas-p01] A world map created by Martin Waldseemüller was the earliest recorded use of the term.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The name was also used (together with the related term *Amerigen*) in the *Cosmographiae Introductio*, apparently written by Matthias Ringmann, in reference to South America.
[src:americas/americas-p01] It was applied to both North and South America by Gerardus Mercator in 1538.
[src:americas/americas-p01] "America" derives from *Americus*, the Latin version of the Italian explorer Amerigo Vespucci's first name.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The feminine form *America* was originally used to refer to the newly discovered continent, which is why it was accorded with the feminine names of the other continents: Asia, Africa, and Europa.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Since the 1950s, however, North America and South America have generally been considered by English speakers as separate continents, and taken together are called *the Americas*, or more rarely *America*.
[src:americas/americas-p01] When conceived as a unitary continent, the form is generally *the continent of America* in the singular.
[src:americas/americas-p01] However, without a clarifying context, singular *America* in English commonly refers to the United States of America.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The region was initially termed America or New India on the Mercator maps.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Speakers of English generally refer to the landmasses of North America and South America as *the Americas*, the *Western Hemisphere*, or the *New World*.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The adjective *American* may be used to indicate something pertaining to the Americas, but this term is primarily used in English to indicate something pertaining to the United States.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Some non-ambiguous alternatives exist, such as the adjective *Pan-American*, or *New Worlder* as a demonym for a resident of the closely related New World.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Use of *America* in the hemispherical sense is sometimes retained, or can occur when translated from other languages.
[src:americas/americas-p01] For example, the Association of National Olympic Committees (ANOC) in Paris maintains a single continental association for "America", represented by one of the five Olympic rings.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Mencken said, "The Latin-Americans use Norteamericano in formal writing, but, save in Panama, prefer nicknames in colloquial speech." To avoid "American" one can use constructed terms in their languages derived from "United States" or even "North America".
[src:americas/americas-p01] In Canada, its southern neighbor is often referred to as "the United States", "the U.S.A.", or (informally) "the States", while U.S. citizens are generally referred to as "Americans".
[src:americas/americas-p01] Most Canadians resent being referred to as "Americans".
[src:americas/americas-p01] In Spanish, *América* is a single continent composed of the subcontinents of *América del Sur* and *América del Norte*, the land bridge of *América Central*, and the islands of the *Antillas*.
[src:americas/americas-p01] *Americano* or *americana* in Spanish refers to a person from *América* in a similar way that in which *europeo* or *europea* refers to a person from *Europa*.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The terms *sudamericano/a*, *centroamericano/a*, *antillano/a* and *norteamericano/a* can be used to more specifically refer to the location where a person may live.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Also, the term *norteamericano* (North American) may refer to a citizen of the United States, though in formal writing it is less common since it is used for the inhabitants of North America.
[src:americas/americas-p01] In Portuguese, *América* is a single continent composed of *América do Sul* (South America), *América Central* (Central America) and *América do Norte* (North America).
[src:americas/americas-p01] It can be ambiguous, as *América* can be used to refer to the United States of America, but is avoided in print and formal environments.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The demonym 'American' (americano) is commonly used in Portuguese to refer to people from the United States, although the terms 'norte-americano', 'estadounidense' or 'estadunidense' also formally exist and are preferred by those who wish to distinguish it from the continental demonym.
[src:americas/americas-p01] In French, the word *américain* may be used for things relating to the Americas; however, similar to English, it is most often used for things relating to the United States, with the term *états-unien* sometimes used for clarity.
[src:americas/americas-p01] *Panaméricain* may be used as an adjective to refer to the Americas without ambiguity.
[src:americas/americas-p01] French speakers may use the noun *Amérique* to refer to the whole landmass as one continent, or two continents, *Amérique du Nord* and *Amérique du Sud*.
[src:americas/americas-p01] In French, *Amérique* is seldom used to refer to the United States, leading to some ambiguity when it is.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Similar to English usage, *les Amériques* or *des Amériques* is used to refer unambiguously to the Americas.
[src:americas/americas-p01] In Dutch, the word *Amerika* mostly refers to the United States.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Although the United States is equally often referred to as *de Verenigde Staten* ("the United States") or *de VS* ("the US"), *Amerika* relatively rarely refers to the Americas, but it is the only commonly used Dutch word for the Americas.
[src:americas/americas-p01] This often leads to ambiguity; and to stress that something concerns the Americas as a whole, Dutch uses a combination, namely *Noord- en Zuid-Amerika* (North and South America).
[src:americas/americas-p01] Latin America and Central America are generally referred to as *Latijns Amerika* and *Midden-Amerika* respectively.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The adjective *Amerikaans* is most often used for things or people relating to the United States.
[src:americas/americas-p01] There are no alternative words to distinguish between things relating to the United States or to the Americas.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Dutch uses the local alternative for things relating to elsewhere in the Americas, such as *Argentijns* for Argentine, etc.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The term *Pre-Columbian* is used especially often in the context of the great indigenous civilizations of the Americas, such as those of Mesoamerica (Olmec, Toltec, Teotihuacano, Zapotec, Mixtec, Aztec, Maya) and the Andean civilizations (Inca, Moche, Chavín, Muisca, Cañari).
[src:americas/americas-p01] Many pre-Columbian civilizations established characteristics and hallmarks which included permanent or urban settlements, agriculture, civic and monumental architecture, and complex societal hierarchies.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Some of these civilizations had long faded by the time of the first permanent European arrivals (c. late 15th–early 16th centuries), and are known only through archeological investigations.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Others were contemporary with this period, and are also known from historical accounts of the time.
[src:americas/americas-p01] A few, such as the Maya, had their own written records.
[src:americas/americas-p01] However, most Europeans of the time viewed such texts as pagan, and much was destroyed in Christian pyres.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Only a few hidden documents remain today, leaving modern historians with glimpses of ancient culture and knowledge.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The first inhabitants migrated into the Americas from Asia.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Habitation sites are known in Alaska and Yukon from at least 20,000 years ago, with suggested ages of up to 40,000 years.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Beyond that, the specifics of the Paleo-Indian migration to and throughout the Americas, including the dates and routes traveled, are subject to ongoing research and discussion.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Widespread habitation of the Americas occurred after the Late Glacial Maximum, from 16,000 to 13,000 years ago.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The traditional theory has been that these early migrants moved into the Beringia land bridge between eastern Siberia and present-day Alaska about 40,000–17,000 years ago, when sea levels were significantly lowered during the Quaternary glaciation.
[src:americas/americas-p01] These people are believed to have followed herds of now-extinct pleistocene megafauna along *ice-free corridors* that stretched between the Laurentide and Cordilleran ice sheets.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Another route proposed is that, either on foot or using primitive boats, they migrated down the Pacific coast to South America.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Evidence of the latter would since have been covered by a sea level rise of hundreds of meters following the last ice age.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Both routes may have been taken, although the genetic evidences suggests a single founding population.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The micro-satellite diversity and distributions specific to South American Indigenous peoples indicates that certain populations have been isolated since the initial colonization of the region.
[src:americas/americas-p01] A second migration occurred after the initial peopling of the Americas; Na Dene speakers, found predominantly in North American groups at varying genetic rates, with the highest frequency found among the Athabaskans at 42%, derive from this second wave.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Linguists and biologists have reached a similar conclusion based on analysis of Amerindian language groups and ABO blood group system distributions.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Then the people of the Arctic small tool tradition, a broad cultural entity that developed along the Alaska Peninsula, around Bristol Bay, and on the eastern shores of the Bering Strait c.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The Arctic small tool tradition, a Paleo-Eskimo culture, branched off into two cultural variants, including the Pre-Dorset and the Independence traditions of Greenland.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The descendants of the Pre-Dorset cultural group, the Dorset culture, were displaced by the final migrants from the Bering sea coast line, the Thule people (the ancestors of modern Inuit), by 1000 CE.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Around the same time as the Inuit migrated into Greenland, Viking settlers began arriving in Greenland in 982 and Vinland shortly thereafter, establishing a settlement at L'Anse aux Meadows, near the northernmost tip of Newfoundland.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Although there had been previous trans-oceanic contact, large-scale European colonization of the Americas began with the first voyage of Christopher Columbus in 1492.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The first Spanish settlement in the Americas was La Isabela in northern Hispaniola.
[src:americas/americas-p01] This town was abandoned shortly after in favor of Santo Domingo de Guzmán, founded in 1496, the oldest American city of European foundation.
[src:americas/americas-p01] This was the base from which the Spanish monarchy administered its new colonies and their expansion.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Santo Domingo was subject to frequent raids by English and French pirates.
[src:americas/americas-p01] On the continent, Panama City on the Pacific coast of Central America, founded on August 15, 1519, played an important role, being the base for the Spanish conquest of South America.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Conquistador Lucas Vázquez de Ayllón established San Miguel de Guadalupe, the first European settlement in what is now the United States, on the Pee Dee River in South Carolina.
[src:americas/americas-p01] During the first half of the 16th century, Spanish colonists conducted raids throughout the Caribbean Basin, bringing captives from Central America, northern South America, and Florida back to Hispaniola and other Spanish settlements.
[src:americas/americas-p01] France, led by Jacques Cartier and Giovanni da Verrazzano, focused primarily on North America.
[src:americas/americas-p01] English explorations of the Americas were led by Giovanni Caboto and Sir Walter Raleigh.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The Dutch in New Netherland confined their operations to Manhattan Island, Long Island, the Hudson River Valley, and what later became New Jersey.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The spread of new diseases brought by Europeans and African slaves killed many of the inhabitants of North America and South America, with a general population crash of Native Americans occurring in the mid-16th century, often well ahead of European contact.
[src:americas/americas-p01] One of the most devastating diseases was smallpox.
[src:americas/americas-p01] European immigrants were often part of state-sponsored attempts to found colonies in the Americas.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Migration continued as people moved to the Americas fleeing religious persecution or seeking economic opportunities.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Millions of individuals were forcibly transported to the Americas as slaves, prisoners or indentured servants.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Decolonization of the Americas began with the American Revolution and the Haitian Revolution in the late 1700s.
[src:americas/americas-p01] This was followed by numerous Latin American wars of independence in the early 1800s.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Between 1811 and 1825, Paraguay, Argentina, Chile, Gran Colombia, the United Provinces of Central America, Mexico, Brazil, Peru, and Bolivia gained independence from Spain and Portugal in armed revolutions.
[src:americas/americas-p01] After the Dominican Republic won independence from Haiti, it was re-annexed by Spain in 1861, but reclaimed its independence in 1865 at the conclusion of the Dominican Restoration War.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The last violent episode of decolonization was the Cuban War of Independence which became the Spanish–American War, which resulted in the independence of Cuba in 1898, and the transfer of sovereignty over Puerto Rico from Spain to the United States.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Peaceful decolonization began with the United States's purchase of Louisiana from France in 1803, Florida from Spain in 1819, Alaska from Russia in 1867, and the Danish West Indies from Denmark in 1916.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Canada became independent of the United Kingdom, starting with the Balfour Declaration of 1926 and the Statute of Westminster 1931 and ending with the patriation of the Canadian Constitution in 1982.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The Dominion of Newfoundland similarly achieved independence under the Balfour Declaration and Statute of Westminster, but relinquished self-rule in 1934.
[src:americas/americas-p01] It was subsequently confederated with Canada in 1949.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The remaining European colonies in the Caribbean began to achieve peaceful independence well after World War II.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Jamaica and Trinidad and Tobago became independent in 1962, and Guyana and Barbados both achieved independence in 1966.
[src:americas/americas-p01] In the 1970s, the Bahamas, Grenada, Dominica, St.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Vincent and the Grenadines all became independent of the United Kingdom, and Suriname became independent of the Netherlands.
[src:americas/americas-p01] Belize, Antigua and Barbuda, and Saint Kitts and Nevis achieved independence from the United Kingdom in the 1980s.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The Americas make up most of the land in Earth's Western Hemisphere.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The northernmost point of the Americas is Kaffeklubben Island, which is the most northerly point of land on Earth.
[src:americas/americas-p01] The southernmost undisputed point is Águila Islet, although the Antarctic islands of Southern Thule are sometimes taken into account.
